015/**
016 * Allows for the use of custom colors with custom names.
017 * <p>
018 * These colors are comparable for equality but the ordering of them is based on
019 * their hex values.
020 * <p>
021 * Has some built in palettes available as SColor arrays.
022 *
023 * @author Eben Howard - http://squidpony.com - howard@squidpony.com
024 * @see SquidColorCenter Another way to manage colors if you don't want to use preallocated instances.
025 */
026public class SColor extends Color implements Serializable {
027    private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;
028    public final String name;
029    private float calculatedFloat;
030

033     * It can be represented as a packed float with the constant {@code -0x1.fffffep126F}.

11328    /**
11329     * A color constant that is fully transparent. The RGB portion is 000000 (black), but should not render when used in
11330     * a method that respects alpha values. When transitioning between colors and ending or starting on transparent, you
11331     * should prefer making a color that has the correct RGB values and also has 0 for the alpha component unless you
11332     * are transitioning from opaque black to this SColor. Using {@link #SColor(int, int, int, int)} will work, as will
11333     * copying the SColor with {@link #cpy()} to get a Color and setting the copy's {@link #a} to 0. If you want to
11334     * obtain a packed float color that has a reduced alpha, you can use {@link #translucentColor(Color, float)} if you
11335     * have a Color or SColor, or its overload that takes a packed float color. This color can be represented as a
11336     * packed float with the constant 0x0.0p0F.
11337     */
11338    public static final SColor TRANSPARENT = new SColor(0, 0, 0, 0, "Transparent");

11438    /**
11439     * An array of SColor values that should all be fairly different from any other in the group.
11440     * This may be useful for tinting things that should be color-coded differently from each other. To get a random
11441     * order for these colors while still guaranteeing that no color will be drawn twice in the first 56 choices, you
11442     * can use {@code OrderedSet<SColor> palette = new OrderedSet<SColor>(SColor.VARIED_PALETTE).shuffle(rng);} (where
11443     * rng is any non-null IRNG) and then get sequential colors from that set with
11444     * {@code int i = 0; SColor color = palette.getAt(i);} , incrementing i before calling getAt again and possibly
11445     * wrapping with {@code i %= 56;} .
11446     * This includes 56 colors, organized in groups of 4 from dark to light in each group:
11447     * <ul>
11448     * <li>0-3: gray group</li>
11449     * <li>4-7: brown group</li>
11450     * <li>8-11: red group</li>
11451     * <li>12-15: pink group</li>
11452     * <li>16-19: magenta/purple group</li>
11453     * <li>20-23: purple/blue-ish group</li>
11454     * <li>24-27: darker blue group</li>
11455     * <li>28-31: lighter blue and blue-green group</li>
11456     * <li>32-35: pure green group</li>
11457     * <li>36-39: grayish-green group</li>
11458     * <li>40-43: yellow-green group</li>
11459     * <li>44-47: yellow group</li>
11460     * <li>48-51: orange group</li>
11461     * <li>52-55: orange-red-pink/salmon/coral group</li>
11462     * </ul>
11463     */
11464    public static final SColor[] VARIED_PALETTE = {
11465            DARK_GRAY, GRAY, LIGHT_GRAY, DB_EGGSHELL,
11466            DB_SEAL_BROWN, BROWNER, DARK_TAN, TAN,
11467            DB_BLOOD, PURE_CRIMSON, RED, IBIS_WING,
11468            TREE_PEONY, DEEP_CERISE, HOT_PINK, PINK,
11469            INDIGO, PURPLE, PSYCHEDELIC_PURPLE, LIGHT_VIOLET,
11470            ROYAL_PURPLE, VIOLET, HALF_PURPLE, LAVENDER_FLORAL,
11471            COBALT, CERULEAN_BLUE, BLUE, CORNFLOWER_BLUE,
11472            LIGHT_BLUE_FLOWER, ROBIN_EGG_BLUE, CYAN, LIGHT_BLUE,
11473            GREEN_BAMBOO, PERSIAN_GREEN, ELECTRIC_GREEN, MINT_GREEN,

11508    /**
11509     * DawnBringer's 256-color Aurora palette, modified slightly to fit one transparent color by removing one gray.
11510     * Aurora is available in <a href="http://pixeljoint.com/forum/forum_posts.asp?TID=26080&KW=">this set of tools</a>
11511     * for a pixel art editor, but it is usable for lots of high-color purposes. The original palette did not have
11512     * names. Naming 256 colors was an ordeal, since many of these colors are well-described by the same name, even when
11513     * two or more can be distinguished visually from each other. Aurora is a good option as a broad-purpose palette
11514     * when using {@link PaletteReducer}, and it is the default there if no palette is specified. For pixel art or
11515     * low-color edits of traditional art, this palette can reproduce a lot of realistic colors and slight changes on
11516     * those colors, with many skin tones (mostly, these are numbered so 1 is the darkest skin tone in a group and
11517     * higher numbers get progressively lighter; the lightest tones are {@link #AURORA_LIGHT_SKIN_9},
11518     * {@link #AURORA_PINK_SKIN_4}, {@link #AURORA_BRONZE_SKIN_4}, and {@link #AURORA_DARK_SKIN_3}, with the LIGHT skin
11519     * tones steadily going from warm and saturated colors at {@link #AURORA_LIGHT_SKIN_1} to more pale at 9, and the
11520     * PINK skin tones meant for accents on some body parts that aren't quite skin-colored, like the lips and ears).
11521     * <a href="https://i.imgur.com/CrI1LyU.png">Preview of all 256 colors, each with the hex number for its index in

11560    /**
11561     * A predefined palette of 198 colors derived from 21 hand-picked hues on the color wheel, with 9 variations on
11562     * saturation and value per hue, along with 9 grayscale colors from black to white. Not all of these colors are
11563     * especially distinguishable from each other; this mainly applies to the darkened colors (DARK_, DRAB_, and
11564     * RICH_) and sometimes the saturated colors (FLUSH_, BRIGHT_, and RICH_). The precise meanings of the terms used:
11565     * CW_ is the base color wheel color with medium saturation and value, CW_FADED_ is desaturated, CW_FLUSH_ is
11566     * saturated, CW_LIGHT_ has value increased, CW_PALE_ has value increased and is desaturated, CW_BRIGHT_ has value
11567     * increased and is saturated, CW_DARK_ has value decreased significantly, CW_DRAB_ has value decreased and is
11568     * desaturated, and CW_RICH_ has value decreased and is saturated. The names for the colors are usually chosen based
11569     * on the appearance of the CW_BRIGHT_ version and the CW_ version, which explains why CW_DRAB_APRICOT doesn't look
11570     * like the apricot fruit, but CW_BRIGHT_APRICOT probably does, depending on monitor brightness.
11571     * <br>
11572     * The array is organized into 21 hue blocks of 9 colors each, going from mid-value to light-value to dark-value
11573     * before moving to the next hue block. It starts at red, moves on to brown and orange, yellow, green, blue, purple,
11574     * and comes almost all the way back around to red. It ends with 9 grayscale colors, from black to white, ordered by
11575     * brightness. The grayscale colors use different names, going from darkest to lightest: CW_BLACK, CW_ALMOST_BLACK,
11576     * CW_GRAY_BLACK, CW_DARK_GRAY, CW_GRAY, CW_LIGHT_GRAY, CW_GRAY_WHITE, CW_ALMOST_WHITE, and CW_WHITE. The CW_BROWN
11577     * group was added after the rest, and has especially low saturation and value, but its hue is at the correct point
11578     * in the order.
11579     * <br>
11580     * <a href="https://i.imgur.com/IWXa2KK.png">Preview of 189 colors (all except grayscale), with names</a>
11581     */

11607    /**
11608     * An alternate version of {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE} that has 16 hues (instead of 21 in the other palette)
11609     * followed by grayscale, with each hue containing 9 colors (there are also 9 grayscale colors). Very similar hues
11610     * have been removed from COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE to try to better support random (or random-like) selection of colors.
11611     * Each section of 9 colors per hue has been reordered as well, going in this order:
11612     * <ol>
11613     *     <li>{@code CW_PALE}, high brightness, low saturation</li>
11614     *     <li>{@code CW_LIGHT}, high brightness, medium saturation</li>
11615     *     <li>{@code CW_BRIGHT}, high brightness, high saturation</li>
11616     *     <li>{@code CW_FADED}, medium brightness, low saturation</li>
11617     *     <li>{@code CW}, medium brightness, medium saturation</li>
11618     *     <li>{@code CW_FLUSH}, medium brightness, high saturation</li>
11619     *     <li>{@code CW_DRAB}, low brightness, low saturation</li>
11620     *     <li>{@code CW_DARK}, low brightness, medium saturation</li>
11621     *     <li>{@code CW_RICH}, low brightness, high saturation</li>
11622     * </ol>
11623     * The grayscale colors go from high brightness to low brightness as well, the reverse of COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE.
11624     * <br>
11625     * You can use some of the utility methods in this class to get colors from this with a good distribution, including
11626     * {@link #randomColorWheel(IRNG, int, int)}, {@link #indexedColorWheel(int, int, int)}, and the overloads of those
11627     * methods with less parameters. If those methods fit your needs, you don't need to read the next section.
11628     * <br>
11629     * This is organized the way it is to allow efficient random color fetching when you know what brightness and
11630     * saturation you want. Example code for this given an {@link IRNG} called {@code rng}, with brightness and
11631     * saturation as ints called {@code bright} and {@code sat} between 0 and 2 inclusive, would be:
11632     * {@code SColor.COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[rng.next(4) * 9 + 3 * bright + sat]}. That code won't ever get a
11633     * grayscale color, but should have an equal chance of choosing any of the 16 hues, with the given saturation and
11634     * brightness. You might want to select colors in a sequence, with a very low chance of similar colors being close
11635     * in the sequence; this can be done in a few ways depending on whether you want saturation and brightness to change
11636     * as well as hue. If you know brightness and saturation as ints between 0 and 2 (inclusive) called {@code bright}
11637     * and {@code sat}, as before, you can go through the 16 hues in a good pattern using a change to the index (an int
11638     * called {@code idx} here): {@code SColor.COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[(idx * 7 & 15) * 9 + 3 * bright + sat]}. If
11639     * you add 1 to idx each time, as in an ordinary for loop, then that code will produce 16 different hues in a fairly
11640     * well-distributed way as idx goes from 0 to 15. If you want brightness to also change in a sequence, you can use
11641     * {@code SColor.COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[((idx * 497) % 48 ^ (idx * 497 >> 2 & 3)) * 3 + sat]} for idx values
11642     * between 0 and 47, inclusive (this is rather complicated due to issues with simpler methods yielding brightness
11643     * changes in an obvious pattern). If you want to select from all 144 non-grayscale colors in a sequence, you can
11644     * try {@code SColor.COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[(idx * 89) % 144 ^ (idx * 89 >> 2 & 3)]}, which will yield all of
11645     * the colors with a good distribution as idx goes from 0 to 143.
11646     */
11647    public static final SColor[] COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED = {
11648            CW_PALE_RED,CW_LIGHT_RED, CW_BRIGHT_RED, CW_FADED_RED, CW_RED, CW_FLUSH_RED, CW_DRAB_RED, CW_DARK_RED, CW_RICH_RED,
11649            CW_PALE_ORANGE,CW_LIGHT_ORANGE, CW_BRIGHT_ORANGE, CW_FADED_ORANGE, CW_ORANGE, CW_FLUSH_ORANGE, CW_DRAB_ORANGE, CW_DARK_ORANGE, CW_RICH_ORANGE,
11650            CW_PALE_BROWN,CW_LIGHT_BROWN, CW_BRIGHT_BROWN, CW_FADED_BROWN, CW_BROWN, CW_FLUSH_BROWN, CW_DRAB_BROWN, CW_DARK_BROWN, CW_RICH_BROWN,
11651            CW_PALE_APRICOT,CW_LIGHT_APRICOT, CW_BRIGHT_APRICOT, CW_FADED_APRICOT, CW_APRICOT, CW_FLUSH_APRICOT, CW_DRAB_APRICOT, CW_DARK_APRICOT, CW_RICH_APRICOT,
11652            CW_PALE_GOLD,CW_LIGHT_GOLD, CW_BRIGHT_GOLD, CW_FADED_GOLD, CW_GOLD, CW_FLUSH_GOLD, CW_DRAB_GOLD, CW_DARK_GOLD, CW_RICH_GOLD,
11653            CW_PALE_YELLOW,CW_LIGHT_YELLOW, CW_BRIGHT_YELLOW, CW_FADED_YELLOW, CW_YELLOW, CW_FLUSH_YELLOW, CW_DRAB_YELLOW, CW_DARK_YELLOW, CW_RICH_YELLOW,

11837    /**
11838     * Contains 9 arrays of 16 SColors each, with each of the outer arrays having a specific saturation and brightness,
11839     * and the inner arrays all going through the 16 "reduced" Color Wheel palette hues. Meant to be used with
11840     * {@link #randomHueSequence()} or its overloads to allow getting various saturation and brightness combinations
11841     * from the same hue. Note that randomHueSequence returns an Integer between 0 and 15, so it would be used to select
11842     * from the inner arrays.
11843     */
11844    public static final SColor[][] COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTES = {
11845            COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_PALE, COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_LIGHT, COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_BRIGHT,
11846            COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_FADED, COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_MID, COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_FLUSH,
11847            COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_DRAB, COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_DARK, COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_RICH
11848    };
11849
11850    /**
11851     * Gets a random color from the palette {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}, with the specified brightness (0 is
11852     * darkest, 1 is middle-bright, 2 is brightest) and saturation (0 is grayest, 1 is mid-saturation, 2 is fully
11853     * saturated), using the specified IRNG.
11854     * @param rng used to choose the hue
11855     * @param bright the brightness to use, from 0 (dark) to 2 (bright)
11856     * @param sat the saturation to use, from 0 (grayish) to 2 (boldly colored)
11857     * @return a randomly selected SColor from {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}
11858     */
11859    public static SColor randomColorWheel(IRNG rng, int bright, int sat)
11860    {
11861        bright = 2 - bright;
11862        bright &= 0x3;
11863        sat &= 0x3;
11864        bright %= 3;
11865        sat %= 3;
11866        return COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[rng.next(4) * 9 + 3 * bright + sat];
11867    }
11868
11869    /**
11870     * Gets a random color from the palette {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}, using the specified IRNG to determine
11871     * saturation, brightness, and hue.
11872     * @param rng used to choose everything
11873     * @return a randomly selected SColor from {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}
11874     */
11875    public static SColor randomColorWheel(IRNG rng)
11876    {
11877        return COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[rng.nextInt(144)];
11878    }
11879    /**
11880     * Gets a color by a shuffled index from the palette {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}, with the specified
11881     * brightness (0 is darkest, 1 is middle-bright, 2 is brightest) and saturation (0 is grayest, 1 is mid-saturation,
11882     * 2 is fully saturated), using the given index to ensure similar index values usually return very different colors.
11883     * This can return up to 16 colors before cycling, if bright and sat stay the same.
11884     * @param idx the index; should change by 1 per color generated to ensure different colors
11885     * @param bright the brightness to use, from 0 (dark) to 2 (bright)
11886     * @param sat the saturation to use, from 0 (grayish) to 2 (boldly colored)
11887     * @return a mathematically selected SColor from {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}
11888     */
11889    public static SColor indexedColorWheel(int idx, int bright, int sat)
11890    {
11891        idx *= 7;
11892        idx &= 0xf;
11893        bright = 2 - bright;
11894        bright &= 0x3;
11895        sat &= 0x3;
11896        bright %= 3;
11897        sat %= 3;
11898        return COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[idx * 9 + 3 * bright + sat];
11899    }
11900    /**
11901     * Gets a color by a shuffled index from the palette {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}, with the specified
11902     * saturation (0 is grayest, 1 is mid-saturation, 2 is fully saturated), using the given index to ensure similar
11903     * index values usually return very different colors. This can return up to 48 colors before cycling, if sat stays
11904     * the same.
11905     * @param idx the index; should change by 1 per color generated to ensure different colors
11906     * @param sat the saturation to use, from 0 (grayish) to 2 (boldly colored)
11907     * @return a mathematically selected SColor from {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}
11908     */
11909    public static SColor indexedColorWheel(int idx, int sat)
11910    {
11911        idx *= 497;
11912        sat &= 0xf;
11913        sat %= 3;
11914        return COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[(idx % 48 ^ (idx >> 2 & 3)) * 3 + sat];
11915    }
11916
11917    /**
11918     * Gets a color by a shuffled index from the palette {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}, using the given index to
11919     * ensure similar index values usually return very different colors. This can return up to 144 colors before
11920     * cycling, which is the total amount of non-grayscale colors in COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED.
11921     * @param idx the index; should change by 1 per color generated to ensure different colors
11922     * @return a mathematically selected SColor from {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED}
11923     */
11924    public static SColor indexedColorWheel(int idx)
11925    {
11926        idx *= 89;
11927        return COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE_REDUCED[idx % 144 ^ (idx >> 2 & 3)];
11928    }
11929
11930    /**
11931     * Returns an infinite Iterator (also an Iterable) over different colors from {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE}, with
11932     * measures taken to avoid returning the same exact SColor twice in a row (but two similar colors could be returned
11933     * in quick succession). See the documentation for {@link GapShuffler} for how you can use the returned infinite
11934     * Iterable; normally you would either call next() on it several times, or use it in a for loop that must at some
11935     * point exit via return or break.
11936     * @param seed a CharSequence, such as a String, to use as a seed; should be fairly long
11937     * @return a GapShuffler over the SColor values in COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE
11938     */
11939    public static GapShuffler<SColor> randomColorSequence(CharSequence seed)
11940    {
11941        return new GapShuffler<>(COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE, seed);
11942    }
11943    /**
11944     * Returns an infinite Iterator (also an Iterable) over different colors from {@link #COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE}, with
11945     * measures taken to avoid returning the same hue of SColor twice in a row (but two similar hues could be returned
11946     * in quick succession). See the documentation for {@link GapShuffler} for how you can use the returned infinite
11947     * Iterable; normally you would either call next() on it several times, or use it in a for loop that must at some
11948     * point exit via return or break. This overload specifies a brightness and saturation to use, and only changes the
11949     * hue; this means there are 16 possible colors this can generate with the same bright and sat parameters.
11950     * @param seed a CharSequence, such as a String, to use as a seed; should be fairly long
11951     * @param bright the brightness to use, from 0 (darkest) to 2 (brightest)
11952     * @param sat the saturation to use, from 0 (grayest) to 2 (boldest)
11953     * @return a GapShuffler over the SColor values in COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE
11954     */
11955    public static GapShuffler<SColor> randomColorSequence(CharSequence seed, int bright, int sat)
11956    {
11957        return new GapShuffler<>(COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTES[((2 - bright) * 3 + sat) % 9], seed);
11958    }

11963     * Iterable; normally you would either call next() on it several times, or use it in a for loop that must at some
11964     * point exit via return or break.
11965     * @param rng the source of randomness for shuffles in the returned sequence; often a {@link squidpony.squidmath.LongPeriodRNG}
11966     * @return a GapShuffler over the SColor values in COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE
11967     */
11968    public static GapShuffler<SColor> randomColorSequence(IRNG rng)
11969    {
11970        return new GapShuffler<>(COLOR_WHEEL_PALETTE, rng);
11971    }

12192    /**
12193     * This array is loaded with all of the colors defined in SColor, in
12194     * arbitrary order.
12195     *
12196     * @deprecated Prefer FULL_PALETTE to this misspelled name; they are equivalent.
12197     */
12198    @Deprecated
12199    public static final SColor[] FULL_PALLET = FULL_PALETTE;
12200
12201    /**
12202     * Indexes into this palette can be used as a placeholder for modules that do not have access to SColor.
12203     * <br>
12204     * This palette has colors at these elements:
12205     * <ul>
12206     * <li>0: Black, also used for backgrounds if not specified</li>
12207     * <li>1: Off-white, used as the default foreground at times</li>
12208     * <li>2: Dark gray for walls</li>
12209     * <li>3: Silver gray for floors</li>
12210     * <li>4: Rust brown for doors</li>
12211     * <li>5: Gray-blue for water</li>
12212     * <li>6: Bright orange for traps</li>
12213     * <li>7: White</li>

12283    /**
12284     * Creates a new color that's the same value as the passed in color.
12285     * Simply sets the name of this SColor to {@link Color#toString()}.
12286     *
12287     * @param color an existing libGDX Color to copy
12288     */
12289    public SColor(Color color) {
12290        super(color);
12291        this.calculatedFloat =  NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(((int)(255 * a) << 24 & 0xfe000000) | ((int)(255 * b) << 16) | ((int)(255 * g) << 8) | ((int)(255 * r)));
12292        name = super.toString();
12293    }

12302    public SColor(Color color, String name) {

12319    }

12395    /**
12396     * Packs the color components into a 32-bit integer with the format ABGR and then converts it to a float.
12397     * Implemented using typed arrays on GWT, which may differ from {@link Color#toFloatBits()} internally but
12398     * should produce identical results. Alpha only keeps the most-significant 7 of 8 bits. You can also
12399     * look at the JavaDocs for almost all predefined SColor values to see what the packed float value is.
12400     * This currently uses a precalculated float instead of recalculating every time, which adds some overhead to
12401     * functions that change an SColor, but these are generally used infrequently.
12402     * 
12403     * @return the packed color as a 32-bit float
12404     */
12405    @Override
12406    public float toFloatBits() {
12407        return calculatedFloat;
12408    }
12409
12410    /**
12411     * Clamps this Color's components to a valid range [0 - 1] and re-calculates the packed float value of this color.
12412     *
12413     * @return this Color for chaining
12414     */
12415    @Override
12416    public Color clamp() { 
12417        super.clamp();
12418        this.calculatedFloat = NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(((int)(255 * a) << 24 & 0xfe000000) | ((int)(255 * b) << 16) | ((int)(255 * g) << 8) | ((int)(255 * r)));
12419        return this;
12420    }
12421
12422    /**
12423     * Modifies the color parameter {@code changing} so its value is the one encoded in {@code value}. The way to
12424     * obtain value for libGDX Color objects is with {@link Color#toFloatBits()}, which uses ABGR order, so this
12425     * does some quick work to convert that to RGBA order and assign that into changing.
12426     *
12427     * @param changing a Color object that will be modified to have the given value
12428     * @param value    a value as a float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
12429     * @return the Color changing, after modification
12430     */
12431    public static Color colorFromFloat(Color changing, float value) {
12432        abgr8888ToColor(changing, value);
12433        return changing;
12434    }
12435
12436    /**
12437     * Produces a new Color that is identical to the one encoded in {@code encoded}. There are various methods in this
12438     * class that return or deal with encoded colors, such as {@link #lerpFloatColors(float, float, float)}, and for
12439     * libGDX Color objects (including SColors) you can use {@link Color#toFloatBits()} to get the float from a Color.
12440     * This method is able to do the reverse of that conversion, and produces a new Color instead of what the overload
12441     * {@link #colorFromFloat(Color, float)} does, which modifies an existing Color. You may want to prefer that
12442     * overload if you have a temporary Color available and can modify it to pass to some method before modifying it
12443     * again later.
12444     *
12445     * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
12446     * @return the Color that can be represented by encoded
12447     */
12448    public static Color colorFromFloat(final float encoded) {
12449        int c = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12450        return new Color(((c & 0x000000ff)) * 0.003921569f, ((c & 0x0000ff00) >>> 8) * 0.003921569f,
12451                ((c & 0x00ff0000) >>> 16) * 0.003921569f, ((c & 0xfe000000) >>> 24) * 0.003937008f);
12452    }

12458     */
12459    public static int redOfFloat(final float encoded)

12525    /**
12526     * Gets the alpha channel value of the given encoded color, as a float from 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.
12527     * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}

12534    /**
12535     * Gets the saturation of the given encoded color, as a float ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.
12536     * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
12537     * @return the saturation of the color from 0.0 (a grayscale color; inclusive) to 1.0 (a
12538     * bright color, exclusive)
12539     */
12540    public static float saturationOfFloat(final float encoded) {
12541        final int e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded),
12542                r = (e & 255), g = (e >>> 8 & 255),
12543                b = (e >>> 16 & 255);//, a = (e >>> 24 & 254) / 254f;
12544        final float min = Math.min(Math.min(r, g), b) * 0.003921569f;   //Min. value of RGB
12545        final float max = Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b) * 0.003921569f;    //Max. value of RGB
12546        final float delta = max - min;                     //Delta RGB value
12547
12548        if ( delta < 0.0001f )                     //This is a gray, no chroma...
12549        {
12550            return 0f;
12551        }
12552        else                                    //Chromatic data...
12553        {
12554            return delta / max;
12555        }
12556    }
12557
12558    /**
12559     * Gets the saturation of this color, as a float ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.
12560     * @return the saturation of the color from 0.0 (a grayscale color; inclusive) to 1.0 (a
12561     * bright color, exclusive)
12562     */
12563    public float saturation() {
12564        return saturation(this);
12565    }
12566
12567    /**
12568     * Gets the saturation of the given Color, as a float ranging from 0.0f to 1.0f, inclusive.
12569     * @return the saturation of the color from 0.0 (a grayscale color; inclusive) to 1.0 (a
12570     * bright color, exclusive)
12571     */
12572    public static float saturation(final Color color) {
12573        final float r = color.r;
12574        final float g = color.g;
12575        final float b = color.b;
12576        final float min = Math.min(Math.min(r, g ), b);   //Min. value of RGB
12577        final float max = Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b);    //Max. value of RGB
12578        final float delta = max - min;                     //Delta RGB value
12579
12580        if ( delta < 0.0001f )                     //This is a gray, no chroma...
12581        {
12582            return 0f;
12583        }
12584        else                                    //Chromatic data...
12585        {
12586            return delta / max;
12587        }
12588    }

12590    /**
12591     * Gets the value (like lightness or brightness) of the given encoded color as a float ranging from 0f to 1f, inclusive.
12592     * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
12593     * @return the value (essentially lightness) of the color from 0.0f (black, inclusive) to
12594     * 1.0f (very bright, inclusive).
12595     */
12596    public static float valueOfFloat(final float encoded)
12597    {
12598        final int e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12599        final int r = (e & 255), g = (e >>> 8 & 255),
12600                b = (e >>> 16 & 255);//, a = (e >>> 24 & 254) / 254f;
12601        return Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b) * 0.003921569f;
12602    }

12604    /**
12605     * Gets the value (like lightness or brightness) of this color as a float ranging from 0f to 1f, inclusive.
12606     * @return the value (essentially lightness) of the color from 0.0f (black, inclusive) to
12607     * 1.0f (very bright, inclusive, including white but also other colors).
12608     */
12609    public float value()
12610    {
12611        return value(this);
12612    }

12614    /**
12615     * Gets the value (like lightness or brightness) of the given Color as a float ranging from 0f to 1f, inclusive.
12616     * @return the value (essentially lightness) of the color from 0.0f (black, inclusive) to
12617     * 1.0f (very bright, inclusive, including white but also other colors).
12618     */
12619    public static float value(final Color color)
12620    {
12621        return Math.max(Math.max(color.r, color.g), color.b);
12622    }

12624    /**
12625     * Gets the hue of the given encoded color, as a float from 0f (inclusive, red and approaching orange if increased)
12626     * to 1f (exclusive, red and approaching purple if decreased).
12627     * @param encoded a color as a packed float that can be obtained by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
12628     * @return The hue of the color from 0.0 (red, inclusive) towards orange, then yellow, and
12629     * eventually to purple before looping back to almost the same red (1.0, exclusive)
12630     */
12631    public static float hueOfFloat(final float encoded) {
12632        final int e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12633        final float r = (e & 255) * 0.003921569f, g = (e >>> 8 & 255) * 0.003921569f,
12634                b = (e >>> 16 & 255) * 0.003921569f;//, a = (e >>> 24 & 254) / 254f;
12635        final float min = Math.min(Math.min(r, g), b);   //Min. value of RGB
12636        final float max = Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b);   //Max value of RGB
12637        final float delta = max - min;                           //Delta RGB value
12638
12639        if ( delta < 0.0001f )                     //This is a gray, no chroma...
12640        {
12641            return 0f;
12642        }
12643        else                                    //Chromatic data...
12644        {
12645            final float rDelta = (((max - r) / 6f) + (delta * 0.5f)) / delta;
12646            final float gDelta = (((max - g) / 6f) + (delta * 0.5f)) / delta;
12647            final float bDelta = (((max - b) / 6f) + (delta * 0.5f)) / delta;
12648
12649            if      (r == max) return (1f + bDelta - gDelta) % 1f;
12650            else if (g == max) return (1f + (1f / 3f) + rDelta - bDelta) % 1f;
12651            else               return (1f + (2f / 3f) + gDelta - rDelta) % 1f;
12652        }
12653    }
12654
12655
12656    /**
12657     * Gets the hue of this color, as a float from 0f (inclusive, red and approaching orange if increased)
12658     * to 1f (exclusive, red and approaching purple if decreased).
12659     * @return The hue of the color from 0.0 (red, inclusive) towards orange, then yellow, and
12660     * eventually to purple before looping back to almost the same red (1.0, exclusive)
12661     */
12662    public float hue() {
12663        return hue(this);
12664    }
12665
12666    /**
12667     * Gets the hue of the given Color, as a float from 0f (inclusive, red and approaching orange if increased)
12668     * to 1f (exclusive, red and approaching purple if decreased).
12669     * @return The hue of the color from 0.0 (red, inclusive) towards orange, then yellow, and
12670     * eventually to purple before looping back to almost the same red (1.0, exclusive)
12671     */
12672    public static float hue(final Color color) {
12673        final float r = color.r;
12674        final float g = color.g;
12675        final float b = color.b;
12676        final float min = Math.min(Math.min(r, g), b);   //Min. value of RGB
12677        final float max = Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b);   //Max value of RGB
12678        final float delta = max - min;                   //Delta RGB value
12679
12680        if ( delta < 0.0001f )                     //This is a gray, no chroma...
12681        {
12682            return 0f;
12683        }
12684        else                                    //Chromatic data...
12685        {
12686            final float rDelta = (((max - r) / 6f) + (delta * 0.5f)) / delta;
12687            final float gDelta = (((max - g) / 6f) + (delta * 0.5f)) / delta;
12688            final float bDelta = (((max - b) / 6f) + (delta * 0.5f)) / delta;
12689
12690            if      (r == max) return (1f + bDelta - gDelta) % 1f;
12691            else if (g == max) return (1f + (1f / 3f) + rDelta - bDelta) % 1f;
12692            else               return (1f + (2f / 3f) + gDelta - rDelta) % 1f;
12693        }
12694    }
12695
12696    /**
12697     * The "luma" of the given Color, which is like its lightness, in YCbCr format; ranges from 0.0f to 1.0f .
12698     * You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCbCr(float, float, float, float)}.
12699     * YCbCr is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cb and
12700     * Cr to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Cb and Cr by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12701     * multiplying Cb and Cr by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and
12702     * so on and so forth.
12703     * @param color a libGDX Color or SColor; will not be modified
12704     * @return the luma as a float from 0.0f to 1.0f
12705     */
12706    public static float luma(final Color color)
12707    {
12708        return (color.r * 0.299f) +
12709               (color.g * 0.587f) +
12710               (color.b * 0.114f);
12711    }
12712
12713    /**
12714     * The "luma" of the given packed float, which is like its lightness, in YCbCr format; ranges from 0.0f to 1.0f .
12715     * You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCbCr(float, float, float, float)}.
12716     * YCbCr is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cb and
12717     * Cr to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Cb and Cr by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12718     * multiplying Cb and Cr by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and
12719     * so on and so forth.
12720     * @param encoded a packed float
12721     * @return the luma as a float from 0.0f to 1.0f
12722     */
12723    public static float lumaOfFloat(final float encoded)
12724    {
12725        final int bits = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12726        return  (bits & 0x000000ff) * (0x1.010102p-8f  * 0.299f) +
12727                (bits & 0x0000ff00) * (0x1.010102p-16f * 0.587f) +
12728                (bits & 0x00ff0000) * (0x1.010102p-24f * 0.114f);
12729    }
12730    /**
12731     * The "Chroma B," or Cb, of the given libGDX Color in YCbCr format; ranges from -0.5f to 0.5f .
12732     * This is related to Chroma R; when Chroma B is high and Chroma R is low, the color is more blue; when Chroma R is
12733     * high and Chroma B is low, the color is more red, when both are low it is more green, and when both are high it is
12734     * more purple. When Chroma R and Chroma B are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because Chroma values
12735     * are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color.
12736     * You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCbCr(float, float, float, float)}.
12737     * YCbCr is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cb and
12738     * Cr to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Cb and Cr by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12739     * multiplying Cb and Cr by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and
12740     * so on and so forth.
12741     * @param color a libGDX Color or SColor
12742     * @return the Chroma B as a float from -0.5f to 0.5f
12743     */
12744    public static float chromaB(final Color color)
12745    {
12746        return (color.r * -0.168736f) +
12747                (color.g * -0.331264f) +
12748                (color.b * 0.5f);
12749    }
12750
12751    /**
12752     * The "Chroma R," or Cr, of the given libGDX Color in YCbCr format; ranges from -0.5f to 0.5f .
12753     * This is related to Chroma B; when Chroma B is high and Chroma R is low, the color is more blue; when Chroma R is
12754     * high and Chroma B is low, the color is more red, when both are low it is more green, and when both are high it is
12755     * more purple. When Chroma R and Chroma B are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because Chroma values
12756     * are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color.
12757     * You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCbCr(float, float, float, float)}.
12758     * YCbCr is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cb and
12759     * Cr to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Cb and Cr by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12760     * multiplying Cb and Cr by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and
12761     * so on and so forth.
12762     * @param color a libGDX Color or SColor
12763     * @return the Chroma R as a float from -0.5f to 0.5f
12764     */
12765    public static float chromaR(final Color color)
12766    {
12767        return (color.r * 0.5f) +
12768                (color.g * -0.418688f) +
12769                (color.b * -0.081312f);
12770    }

12772    /**
12773     * The "Chroma B," or Cb, of the given packed float in YCbCr format; ranges from -0.5f to 0.5f .
12774     * This is related to Chroma R; when Chroma B is high and Chroma R is low, the color is more blue; when Chroma R is
12775     * high and Chroma B is low, the color is more red, when both are low it is more green, and when both are high it is
12776     * more purple. When Chroma R and Chroma B are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because Chroma values
12777     * are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color.
12778     * You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCbCr(float, float, float, float)}.
12779     * YCbCr is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cb and
12780     * Cr to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Cb and Cr by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12781     * multiplying Cb and Cr by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and
12782     * so on and so forth.
12783     * @param encoded a packed float
12784     * @return the Chroma B as a float from -0.5f to 0.5f
12785     */
12786    public static float chromaBOfFloat(final float encoded)
12787    {
12788        final int bits = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12789        return  (bits & 0x000000ff) * (0x1.010102p-8f  * -0.168736f) +
12790                (bits & 0x0000ff00) * (0x1.010102p-16f * -0.331264f) +
12791                (bits & 0x00ff0000) * (0x1.010102p-24f * 0.5f);
12792    }
12793    /**
12794     * The "Chroma R," or Cr, of the given packed float in YCbCr format; ranges from -0.5f to 0.5f .
12795     * This is related to Chroma B; when Chroma B is high and Chroma R is low, the color is more blue; when Chroma R is
12796     * high and Chroma B is low, the color is more red, when both are low it is more green, and when both are high it is
12797     * more purple. When Chroma R and Chroma B are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because Chroma values
12798     * are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color.
12799     * You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCbCr(float, float, float, float)}.
12800     * YCbCr is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cb and
12801     * Cr to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Cb and Cr by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12802     * multiplying Cb and Cr by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and
12803     * so on and so forth.
12804     * @param encoded a packed float
12805     * @return the Chroma R as a float from -0.5f to 0.5f
12806     */
12807    public static float chromaROfFloat(final float encoded)
12808    {
12809        final int bits = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12810        return  (bits & 0x000000ff) * (0x1.010102p-8f  * 0.5f) +
12811                (bits & 0x0000ff00) * (0x1.010102p-16f * -0.418688f) +
12812                (bits & 0x00ff0000) * (0x1.010102p-24f * -0.081312f);
12813    }

12815    /**
12816     * The "luminance" of the given packed float, which is like its lightness, in YCoCg format; ranges from 0.0f to
12817     * 1.0f . You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCoCg(float, float, float, float)}.
12818     * YCoCg is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Co and
12819     * Cg to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Co and Cg by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12820     * multiplying Co and Cg by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing
12821     * luminance, and so on and so forth. YCoCg is also a little more efficient to process than YCbCr, which other
12822     * methods like {@link #floatGetYCbCr(float, float, float, float)} use. This might not be as perceptually accurate
12823     * at determining lightness as {@link #lumaOfFloat(float)}.
12824     * @param encoded a packed float
12825     * @return the luminance as a float from 0.0f to 1.0f
12826     */
12827    public static float luminanceYCoCg(final float encoded)
12828    {
12829        final int bits = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12830        return ((bits & 0x000000ff) + ((bits & 0x0000ff00) >>> 7) + ((bits & 0x00ff0000) >>> 16)) * 0x1.010102p-10f;
12831    }
12832    /**
12833     * The "luma" of the given packed float, which is like its lightness, in YCwCm format; ranges from 0.0f to
12834     * 1.0f . You can go back to an RGB color as a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCwCm(float, float, float, float)}.
12835     * YCwCm is useful for modifications to colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cw and
12836     * Cm to 0, you can desaturate by multiplying Cw and Cm by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by
12837     * multiplying Cw and Cm by a number greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and
12838     * so on and so forth. Unlike YCoCg and YCbCr, there are aesthetic reasons to adjust just one of Cw or Cm for some
12839     * effect; multiplying Cw by a number greater than 1 will make warm colors warmer and cool colors cooler, for
12840     * instance. This might not be as perceptually accurate at determining lightness as {@link #lumaOfFloat(float)}.
12841     * @param encoded a packed float
12842     * @return the luma as a float from 0.0f to 1.0f
12843     */
12844    public static float lumaYCwCm(final float encoded)
12845    {
12846        final int bits = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encoded);
12847        return (bits & 0xFF) * 0x3p-11f + (bits >>> 8 & 0xFF) * 0x1p-9f + (bits >>> 16 & 0xFF) * 0x1p-11f;
12848    }

12999     * greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and so on and so forth. Unlike

13011     * The "chroma mild" of the given libGDX Color, which when combined with chroma warm describes the shade and
13012     * saturation of a color, in YCwCm format; ranges from -1f to 1f . You can go back to an RGB color as
13013     * a packed float with {@link #floatGetYCwCm(float, float, float, float)}. YCwCm is useful for modifications to
13014     * colors because you can get a grayscale version of a color by setting Cw and Cm to 0, you can desaturate by
13015     * multiplying Cw and Cm by a number between 0 and 1, you can oversaturate by multiplying Cw and Cm by a number
13016     * greater than 1, you can lighten or darken by increasing or decreasing luma, and so on and so forth. Unlike
13017     * YCoCg and YCbCr, there are aesthetic reasons to adjust just one of Cw or Cm for some effect; multiplying Cw by
13018     * a number greater than 1 will make warm colors warmer and cool colors cooler, for instance.

13028    /**
13029     * A color distance metric between two colors as packed floats, without performing a square root on the result.
13030     * The returned int can be used directly, with a typical difference of 5 or greater meaning there is a perceptible
13031     * difference between the two colors, or you can get its square root to have a more typical metric where differences
13032     * can be compared to modifications of other differences. If you only care about whether a difference is above or
13033     * below some threshold (or which color is closest to another, not exactly how close they are), then you don't need
13034     * to get the square root. Does not consider the alpha of the compared colors.
13035     * <br>
13036     * Uses <a href="https://www.compuphase.com/cmetric.htm">this algorithm</a>.
13037     * @param color1 a color as a packed float
13038     * @param color2 a color as a packed float
13039     * @return the squared difference of the two colors, as an int; you can get the square root of this if you want to
13040     */
13041    public static int difference2(float color1, float color2)
13042    {
13043        int bits1 = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(color1), bits2 = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(color2);
13044        int rmean = ((bits1 & 0xFF) + (bits2 & 0xFF)) >> 1;
13045        int r = (bits1 & 0xFF) - (bits2 & 0xFF);
13046        int g = (bits1 >>> 8 & 0xFF) - (bits2 >>> 8 & 0xFF);
13047        int b = (bits1 >>> 16 & 0xFF) - (bits2 >>> 16 & 0xFF);
13048        return (((512+rmean)*r*r)>>8) + 4*g*g + (((767-rmean)*b*b)>>8);
13049    }
13050    /**
13051     * A color distance metric between two libGDX Colors (or SColors), without performing a square root on the result.
13052     * The returned int can be used directly, with a typical difference of 5 or greater meaning there is a perceptible
13053     * difference between the two colors, or you can get its square root to have a more typical metric where differences
13054     * can be compared to modifications of other differences. If you only care about whether a difference is above or
13055     * below some threshold (or which color is closest to another, not exactly how close they are), then you don't need
13056     * to get the square root. Does not consider the alpha of the compared colors.
13057     * <br>
13058     * Uses <a href="https://www.compuphase.com/cmetric.htm">this algorithm</a>.
13059     * @param color1 a libGDX Color
13060     * @param color2 a libGDX Color
13061     * @return the squared difference of the two colors, as an int; you can get the square root of this if you want to
13062     */
13063    public static int difference2(Color color1, Color color2)
13064    {
13065        int r1 = (int)(color1.r * 255), r2 = (int)(color2.r * 255);
13066        int rmean = (r1 + r2) >> 1;
13067        int r = r1 - r2;
13068        int g = (int)(color1.g * 255) - (int)(color2.g * 255);
13069        int b = (int)(color1.b * 255) - (int)(color2.b * 255);
13070        return (((512+rmean)*r*r)>>8) + 4*g*g + (((767-rmean)*b*b)>>8);
13071    }
13072    /**
13073     * A color distance metric between a packed float color and a libGDX Color (or SColor), without performing a square
13074     * root on the result. The returned int can be used directly, with a typical difference of 5 or greater meaning
13075     * there is a perceptible difference between the two colors, or you can get its square root to have a more typical
13076     * metric where differences can be compared to modifications of other differences. If you only care about whether a
13077     * difference is above or below some threshold (or which color is closest to another, not exactly how close they
13078     * are), then you don't need to get the square root. Does not consider the alpha of the compared colors.
13079     * <br>
13080     * Uses <a href="https://www.compuphase.com/cmetric.htm">this algorithm</a>. This method produces equivalent output
13081     * to {@link #difference2(float, float)} when color2 is converted to a float with {@link #toFloatBits()}; the output
13082     * is also equivalent to {@link #difference2(Color, Color)} when color1 is converted to a Color with
13083     * {@link Color#abgr8888ToColor(Color, float)} or {@link SColor#colorFromFloat(float)}. It can be useful when you
13084     * need to mix Color-based APIs such as {@link SquidColorCenter} with float-based ones such as the static methods
13085     * in this class.
13086     * @param color1 a packed float color
13087     * @param color2 a libGDX Color
13088     * @return the squared difference of the two colors, as an int; you can get the square root of this if you want to
13089     */
13090    public static int difference2(float color1, Color color2)
13091    {
13092        int bits1 = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(color1);
13093        int r1 = (bits1 & 0xFF), r2 = (int)(color2.r * 255);
13094        int rmean = (r1 + r2) >> 1;
13095        int r = r1 - r2;
13096        int g = (bits1 >>> 8 & 0xFF) - (int)(color2.g * 255);
13097        int b = (bits1 >>> 16 & 0xFF) - (int)(color2.b * 255);
13098        return (((512+rmean)*r*r)>>8) + 4*g*g + (((767-rmean)*b*b)>>8);
13099    }
13100
13101    public static float differenceYCbCr(final int color1, final int color2)
13102    {
13103        final int r1 = color1 >>> 24, r2 = color2 >>> 24,
13104                g1 = color1 >>> 16 & 255, g2 = color2 >>> 16 & 255,
13105                b1 = color1 >>> 8 & 255, b2 = color2 >>> 8 & 255;
13106        final float
13107                y1 = r1 * 0.299f + g1 * 0.587f + b1 * 0.114f,
13108                y2 = r2 * 0.299f + g2 * 0.587f + b2 * 0.114f,
13109                cr1 = r1 * 0.5f + g1 * -0.418688f + b1 * -0.081312f,
13110                cr2 = r2 * 0.5f + g2 * -0.418688f + b2 * -0.081312f,
13111                cb1 = r1 * -0.168736f + g1 * -0.331264f + b1 * 0.5f,
13112                cb2 = r2 * -0.168736f + g2 * -0.331264f + b2 * 0.5f,
13113                y = y2 - y1, cb = cb2 - cb1, cr = cr2 - cr1;
13114        return y * y + cb * cb + cr * cr;
13115    }
13116
13117    public static float differenceYCbCr(final int color1, int r2, int g2, int b2)
13118    {
13119        final int r1 = color1 >>> 24,
13120                g1 = color1 >>> 16 & 255,
13121                b1 = color1 >>> 8 & 255;
13122        final float
13123                y1 = r1 * 0.299f + g1 * 0.587f + b1 * 0.114f,
13124                y2 = r2 * 0.299f + g2 * 0.587f + b2 * 0.114f,
13125                cr1 = r1 * 0.5f + g1 * -0.418688f + b1 * -0.081312f,
13126                cr2 = r2 * 0.5f + g2 * -0.418688f + b2 * -0.081312f,
13127                cb1 = r1 * -0.168736f + g1 * -0.331264f + b1 * 0.5f,
13128                cb2 = r2 * -0.168736f + g2 * -0.331264f + b2 * 0.5f,
13129                y = y2 - y1, cb = cb2 - cb1, cr = cr2 - cr1;
13130        return y * y + cb * cb + cr * cr;
13131    }
13132
13133    public static float differenceYCbCr(final int r1, final int r2, final int g1, final int g2, final int b1, final int b2)
13134    {
13135        final float
13136                y1 = r1 * 0.299f + g1 * 0.587f + b1 * 0.114f,
13137                y2 = r2 * 0.299f + g2 * 0.587f + b2 * 0.114f,
13138                cr1 = r1 * 0.5f + g1 * -0.418688f + b1 * -0.081312f,
13139                cr2 = r2 * 0.5f + g2 * -0.418688f + b2 * -0.081312f,
13140                cb1 = r1 * -0.168736f + g1 * -0.331264f + b1 * 0.5f,
13141                cb2 = r2 * -0.168736f + g2 * -0.331264f + b2 * 0.5f,
13142                y = y2 - y1, cb = cb2 - cb1, cr = cr2 - cr1;
13143        return y * y + cb * cb + cr * cr;
13144    }

13156    /**
13157     * Given a Color or SColor object and an alpha multiplier to affect that color (between 0f and 1f, inclusive and
13158     * clamped in that range), this makes a packed float color that has the same red, green, and blue channels but has
13159     * its own alpha multiplied by {@code alpha}, without constructing any objects along the way.
13160     *
13161     * @param color  a libGDX Color (or SColor); will not be modified
13162     * @param alpha  between 0.0 and 1.0 inclusive, the alpha to multiply the color's own alpha by
13163     * @return a color encoded as a packed float, using color's RGB channels but with its A channel times {@code alpha}
13164     */
13165    public static float multiplyAlpha(Color color, float alpha) {
13166        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(color.toIntBits() & 0xFFFFFF
13167                | (MathUtils.clamp((int) (color.a * 255f * alpha), 0, 255) << 24 & 0xFE000000));
13168    }
13169
13170    /**
13171     * Given a color stored as a packed float and an alpha multiplier to affect that color (between 0f and 1f, inclusive
13172     * and clamped in that range), this makes a packed float color that has the same red, green, and blue channels but
13173     * has its own alpha multiplied by {@code alpha}, without constructing any objects along the way.
13174     *
13175     * @param encodedColor a color encoded as a packed float, as by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
13176     * @param alpha  between 0.0 and 1.0 inclusive, the alpha to multiply the color's own alpha by
13177     * @return a color encoded as a packed float, using color's RGB channels but with its A channel times {@code alpha}
13178     */
13179    public static float multiplyAlpha(float encodedColor, float alpha) {
13180        final int bits = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encodedColor);
13181        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(bits & 0xFFFFFF
13182                | (MathUtils.clamp((int) ((bits >>> 24) * alpha), 0, 255) << 24 & 0xFE000000));
13183    }

13185    /**
13186     * Given a Color or SColor object and a desired alpha to set for that color (between 0f and 1f, inclusive and
13187     * clamped in that range), this makes a packed float color that has the same red, green, and blue channels but has
13188     * been set to the given alpha, without constructing any objects along the way.
13189     *
13190     * @param color  a libGDX Color (or SColor); will not be modified
13191     * @param alpha  between 0.0 and 1.0 inclusive, the alpha to set into the returned packed color
13192     * @return a color encoded as a packed float, using color's RGB channels and the given alpha
13193     */
13194    public static float translucentColor(Color color, float alpha) {
13195        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(color.toIntBits() & 0xFFFFFF
13196                | (MathUtils.clamp((int) (255f * alpha), 0, 255) << 24 & 0xFE000000));
13197    }

13199    /**
13200     * Given a color stored as a packed float, and a desired alpha to set for that color (between 0.0 and 1.0, inclusive
13201     * and clamped in that range), this makes a new float that has the same red, green, and blue channels but has been
13202     * set to the given alpha, without constructing any objects along the way.
13203     *
13204     * @param encodedColor a color encoded as a packed float, as by {@link Color#toFloatBits()}
13205     * @param alpha        between 0.0 and 1.0 inclusive, the alpha to set into the returned packed color
13206     * @return another color encoded as a packed float, using encodedColor's RGB channels and the given alpha
13207     */
13208    public static float translucentColor(float encodedColor, float alpha) {
13209        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(NumberTools.floatToIntBits(encodedColor) & 0xFFFFFF
13210                | (MathUtils.clamp((int) (255f * alpha), 0, 255) << 24 & 0xFE000000));
13211    }
13212
13213    private static final char[] digits = {
13214            '0', '1', '2', '3', '4', '5', '6', '7',
13215            '8', '9', 'A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'E', 'F'};
13216
13217    /**
13218     * Stores the value of color in the char[] {@code changing}, using RGBA8888 format with two hex digits per channel.
13219     * This means that changing must be at least length 8 (this doesn't check for efficiency reasons), and that the
13220     * first two chars represent the red channel from 0 to 255, then the next two are green, then blue. The alpha
13221     * channel is a special case because it represents alpha values between 0 and 254, and effectively rounds down to
13222     * the nearest even number if an odd number value was somehow given to it. For example, opaque white will be shown
13223     * as "FFFFFFFE", and pure red with 50% alpha will be shown as "FF00007E".
13224     * <br>
13225     * The value of {@code color} should be the same type used internally in libGDX and SquidLib, that is, an ABGR
13226     * packed float that could be passed directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}.
13227     *
13228     * @param changing a char array that will be changed in place; must not be null and must have length of at least 8
13229     * @param color    a color
13230     * @return the char array parameter changing, after modifications to store an RGBA8888 color as hex
13231     */
13232    public static char[] floatToChars(final char[] changing, final float color) {
13233        final int i = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(color);
13234        changing[1] = digits[i & 15];
13235        changing[0] = digits[(i >>> 4) & 15];
13236        changing[3] = digits[(i >>> 8) & 15];
13237        changing[2] = digits[(i >>> 12) & 15];
13238        changing[5] = digits[(i >>> 16) & 15];
13239        changing[4] = digits[(i >>> 20) & 15];
13240        changing[7] = digits[(i >>> 24) & 14]; // mask is 14 due to libGDX avoiding floats that can be NaN
13241        changing[6] = digits[i >>> 28];
13242        return changing;
13243    }
13244
13245    /**
13246     * Meant for usage with {@link #floatToChars(char[], float)}, this will take 8 chars from {@code data} starting at
13247     * {@code offset}, read them as as an RGBA8888 32-bit integer in hexadecimal format, and return that integer in
13248     * RGBA8888 format. Some parts of libGDX use and expect RGBA8888 order, such as most constructors for Color and
13249     * {@link Color#set(int)}, while others use ABGR8888 (often with packed floats), like
13250     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}, which is the fastest and least wasteful way to set
13251     * the current color used by a Batch for tinting.
13252     *
13253     * @param data   a char array that must not be null; the first 8 chars after offset should be an RGBA8888 hex integer
13254     * @param offset where to start reading from in data; there must be at least 8 items between offset and data.length
13255     * @return an int in RGBA8888 format
13256     */
13257    public static int charsToRGBA(final char[] data, final int offset) {
13258        return StringKit.intFromHex(data, offset, Math.min(data.length, offset + 8));
13259    }

13262     * Meant for usage with {@link #floatToChars(char[], float)}, this will take 8 chars from {@code data}, read them as
13263     * as an RGBA8888 32-bit integer in hexadecimal format, and return that integer in RGBA8888 format. Some parts of
13264     * libGDX use and expect RGBA8888 order, such as most constructors for Color and {@link Color#set(int)}, while
13265     * others use ABGR8888 (often with packed floats), like {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)},
13266     * which is the fastest and least wasteful way to set the current color used by a Batch for tinting.

13271    public static int charsToRGBA(final char[] data) {
13272        return StringKit.intFromHex(data, 0, Math.min(data.length, 8));
13273    }

13357    /**
13358     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 4 RGBA float components. LibGDX expects ABGR format
13359     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
13360     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
13361     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
13362     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
13363     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
13364     *
13365     * @param r a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for red
13366     * @param g a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for green
13367     * @param b a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for blue
13368     * @param a a float from 0.0 to 1.0 for alpha/opacity
13369     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
13370     */
13371    public static float floatGet(float r, float g, float b, float a) {
13372        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(((int) (a * 255) << 24 & 0xFE000000) | ((int) (b * 255) << 16)
13373                | ((int) (g * 255) << 8) | (int) (r * 255));
13374    }

13376    /**
13377     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format long. LibGDX expects ABGR format
13378     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
13379     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
13380     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
13381     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
13382     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
13383     * <br>
13384     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format longs that you
13385     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
13386     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
13387     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
13388     *
13389     * @param c a long with format {@code 32 unused bits, 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
13390     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
13391     */
13392    public static float floatGet(long c) {
13393        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((int) ((c >>> 24 & 0xff) | (c >>> 8 & 0xff00) | (c << 8 & 0xff0000)
13394                | (c << 24 & 0xfe000000)));
13395    }

13397    /**
13398     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given an RGBA8888-format int. LibGDX expects ABGR format
13399     * in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR, or ARGB. Generally,
13400     * packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed directly to
13401     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)} without constructing intermediate objects.
13402     * SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
13403     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
13404     * <br>
13405     * This method is probably not what you want unless you specifically have RGBA8888-format ints that you
13406     * want converted to packed floats. You probably should look at {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)} if
13407     * you have alpha and/or float components, or {@link #floatGetI(int, int, int)} for the common case of the 3 RGB
13408     * components as ints and alpha simply opaque.
13409     *
13410     * @param c an int with format {@code 8 red bits, 8 green bits, 8 blue bits, 7 alpha bits, 1 unused bit}
13411     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
13412     */
13413    public static float floatGet(int c) {
13414        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(Integer.reverseBytes(c) & 0xFEFFFFFF);
13415    }
