13417    /**
13418     * Gets a packed float representation of a color given as 3 RGB int components, setting alpha to opaque. LibGDX
13419     * expects ABGR format in some places, but not all, and it can be confusing to track when it wants RGBA, ABGR,
13420     * or ARGB. Generally, packed floats like what this returns are ABGR format, the kind that can be passed
13421     * directly to {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)} without constructing intermediate
13422     * objects. SquidPanel also uses floats internally instead of LibGDX Color objects in its internal 2D array that
13423     * associates colors to cells; this has changed from earlier releases and should be much more efficient.
13424     *
13425     * @param r an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for red
13426     * @param g an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for green
13427     * @param b an int from 0 to 255 (both inclusive) for blue
13428     * @return a packed float that can be given to the setColor method in LibGDX's Batch classes
13429     */
13430    public static float floatGetI(int r, int g, int b) {
13431        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((r & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (b << 16 & 0xff0000)
13432                | 0xfe000000); //rgbToFloatColor((b & 0xff) | (g << 8 & 0xff00) | (r << 16));
13433    }
13434
13435    /**
13436     * Gets a color as a packed float given floats representing hue, saturation, value, and opacity.
13437     * All parameters should normally be between 0 and 1 inclusive, though hue is tolerated if it is negative down to
13438     * -6f at the lowest or positive up to any finite value, though precision loss may affect the color if the hue is
13439     * too large. A hue of 0 is red, progressively higher hue values go to orange, yellow, green, blue, and purple
13440     * before wrapping around to red as it approaches 1. A saturation of 0 is grayscale, a saturation of 1 is brightly
13441     * colored, and values close to 1 will usually appear more distinct than values close to 0, especially if the
13442     * hue is different (saturation below 0.0039f is treated specially here, and does less work to simply get a color
13443     * between black and white with the given opacity). The value is similar to lightness; a value of 0.0039 or less is
13444     * always black (also using a shortcut if this is the case, respecting opacity), while a value of 1 is as bright as
13445     * the color gets with the given saturation and value. To get a value of white, you would need both a value of 1 and
13446     * a saturation of 0.
13447     *
13448     * @param hue        0f to 1f, color wheel position
13449     * @param saturation 0f to 1f, 0f is grayscale and 1f is brightly colored
13450     * @param value      0f to 1f, 0f is black and 1f is bright or light
13451     * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
13452     * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
13453     */
13454    public static float floatGetHSV(float hue, float saturation, float value, float opacity) {
13455        if (saturation <= 0.0039f) {
13456            return floatGet(value, value, value, opacity);
13457        } else if (value <= 0.0039f) {
13458            return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((int) (opacity * 255f) << 24 & 0xFE000000);
13459        } else {
13460            final float h = ((hue + 6f) % 1f) * 6f;
13461            final int i = (int) h;
13462            value = MathUtils.clamp(value, 0f, 1f);
13463            saturation = MathUtils.clamp(saturation, 0f, 1f);
13464            final float a = value * (1 - saturation);
13465            final float b = value * (1 - saturation * (h - i));
13466            final float c = value * (1 - saturation * (1 - (h - i)));
13467
13468            switch (i) {
13469                case 0:
13470                    return floatGet(value, c, a, opacity);
13471                case 1:
13472                    return floatGet(b, value, a, opacity);
13473                case 2:
13474                    return floatGet(a, value, c, opacity);
13475                case 3:
13476                    return floatGet(a, b, value, opacity);
13477                case 4:
13478                    return floatGet(c, a, value, opacity);
13479                default:
13480                    return floatGet(value, a, b, opacity);
13481            }
13482        }
13483    }
13484    /**
13485     * Gets a color as a packed float given floats representing luma (Y, akin to lightness), blue chroma (Cb, one of two
13486     * kinds of chroma used here), red chroma (Cr, the other kind of chroma), and opacity. Luma should be between 0 and
13487     * 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors including but not limited to black, and 1 used for very light
13488     * colors including but not limited to white. The two chroma values range from -0.5 to 0.5, and only make sense when
13489     * used together. When Chroma B is high and Chroma R is low, the color is more blue; when Chroma R is high and
13490     * Chroma B is low, the color is more red, when both are low it is more green, and when both are high it is more
13491     * purple. When Chroma R and Chroma B are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because Chroma values are
13492     * centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color.
13493     *
13494     * @param luma       0f to 1f, lightness (see {@link #lumaOfFloat(float)})
13495     * @param chromaB    -0.5f to 0.5f, "blueness" of chroma component, with 0.5 more blue (see {@link #chromaBOfFloat(float)})
13496     * @param chromaR    -0.5f to 0.5f, "redness" of chroma component, with 0.5 more red (see {@link #chromaROfFloat(float)})
13497     * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
13498     * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
13499     */
13500    public static float floatGetYCbCr(float luma, float chromaB, float chromaR, float opacity) {
13501        if (chromaR >= -0.0039f && chromaR <= 0.0039f && chromaB >= -0.0039f && chromaB <= 0.0039f) {
13502            return floatGet(luma, luma, luma, opacity);
13503        }
13504        return floatGet(MathUtils.clamp(luma + chromaR * 1.402f, 0f, 1f),
13505                MathUtils.clamp(luma - chromaB * 0.344136f - chromaR * 0.714136f, 0f, 1f),
13506                MathUtils.clamp(luma + chromaB * 1.772f, 0f, 1f),
13507                opacity);
13508    }
13509    /**
13510     * Gets a libGDX Color given floats representing luma (Y, akin to lightness), blue chroma (Cb, one of two
13511     * kinds of chroma used here), red chroma (Cr, the other kind of chroma), and opacity. Luma should be between 0 and
13512     * 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors including but not limited to black, and 1 used for very light
13513     * colors including but not limited to white. The two chroma values range from -0.5 to 0.5, and only make sense when
13514     * used together. When Chroma B is high and Chroma R is low, the color is more blue; when Chroma R is high and
13515     * Chroma B is low, the color is more red, when both are low it is more green, and when both are high it is more
13516     * purple. When Chroma R and Chroma B are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because Chroma values are
13517     * centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color. This
13518     * allocates a new Color and clamps its r, g, b, and a values to between 0 and 1, regardless of input range.
13519     *
13520     * @param luma       0f to 1f, lightness (see {@link #luma(Color)})
13521     * @param chromaB    -0.5f to 0.5f, "blueness" of chroma component, with 0.5 more blue (see {@link #chromaB(Color)})
13522     * @param chromaR    -0.5f to 0.5f, "redness" of chroma component, with 0.5 more red (see {@link #chromaR(Color)})
13523     * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
13524     * @return a libGDX Color with the given properties
13525     */
13526    public static Color ycbcr(float luma, float chromaB, float chromaR, float opacity){
13527        return new Color(luma + chromaR * 1.402f, luma - chromaB * 0.344136f - chromaR * 0.714136f, luma + chromaB * 1.772f, opacity);
13528    }
13529
13530    /**
13531     * Gets a color as a packed float given floats representing luminance (Y, akin to lightness), orange chrominance
13532     * (Co, one of two kinds of chroma used here), green chrominance (Cg, the other kind of chroma), and opacity.
13533     * Luminance should be between 0 and 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors including but not limited to
13534     * black, and 1 used for very light colors including but not limited to white. The two chrominance values range from
13535     * -0.5 to 0.5, and only make sense when used together. When Co is high and Cg is low, the color is more reddish;
13536     * when both are low it is more bluish, and when Cg is high the color tends to be greenish (it can be more cyan or
13537     * more yellow depending on Co, but mostly when Y isn't low). When Co and Cg are both near 0.0f, the color is closer
13538     * to gray. Because chrominance values are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the
13539     * colorfulness of the color.
13540     * <br>
13541     * This method clamps the resulting color's RGB values, so any values can technically be given to this as y, co, and
13542     * cg, but they will only be reversible from the returned float color to the original Y, Cb, and Cr values if the
13543     * original values were in the range that {@link #chrominanceOrange(float)}, {@link #chrominanceGreen(float)}, and
13544     * {@link #luminanceYCoCg(float)} return.
13545     *
13546     * @param y          0f to 1f, luminance or Y component of YCoCg
13547     * @param co         -0.5f to 0.5f, "chrominance orange" or Co component of YCoCg, with 0.5f more orange
13548     * @param cg         -0.5f to 0.5f, "chrominance green" or Cg component of YCoCg, with 0.5f more green
13549     * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
13550     * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
13551     */
13552    public static float floatGetYCoCg(float y, float co, float cg, float opacity) {
13553//        if (luma <= 0.0039f) {
13554//            return floatGet(0f, 0f, 0f, opacity);
13555//        } else if (luma >= 0.9961f) {
13556//            return floatGet(1f, 1f, 1f, opacity);
13557//        }
13558//        if (co >= -0.0039f && co <= 0.0039f && cg >= -0.0039f && cg <= 0.0039f) {
13559//            return floatGet(y, y, y, opacity);
13560//        }
13561        /*
13562t = Y - Cg;
13563R = t + Co;
13564G = Y + Cg;
13565B = t - Co;
13566         */
13567        final float t = y - cg;
13568        return floatGet(MathUtils.clamp(t + co, 0f, 1f),
13569                MathUtils.clamp(y + cg, 0f, 1f),
13570                MathUtils.clamp(t - co, 0f, 1f),
13571                opacity);
13572    }
13573    /**
13574     * Gets a color as a packed float given floats representing luminance (Y, akin to lightness), orange chrominance
13575     * (Co, one of two kinds of chroma used here), green chrominance (Cg, the other kind of chroma), and opacity.
13576     * Luminance should be between 0 and 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors including but not limited to
13577     * black, and 1 used for very light colors including but not limited to white. The two chrominance values range from
13578     * -0.5 to 0.5, and only make sense when used together. When Co is high and Cg is low, the color is more reddish;
13579     * when both are low it is more bluish, and when Cg is high the color tends to be greenish (it can be more cyan or
13580     * more yellow depending on Co, but mostly when Y isn't low). When Co and Cg are both near 0.0f, the color is closer
13581     * to gray. Because chrominance values are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply them by a value like 0.5f to halve the
13582     * colorfulness of the color.
13583     * <br>
13584     * This method clamps the resulting color's RGB values, so any values can technically be given to this as y, co, and
13585     * cg, but they will only be reversible from the returned float color to the original Y, Cb, and Cr values if the
13586     * original values were in the range that {@link #chrominanceOrange(float)}, {@link #chrominanceGreen(float)}, and
13587     * {@link #luminanceYCoCg(float)} return.
13588     *
13589     * @param y          0f to 1f, luminance or Y component of YCoCg
13590     * @param co         -0.5f to 0.5f, "chrominance orange" or Co component of YCoCg, with 0.5f more orange
13591     * @param cg         -0.5f to 0.5f, "chrominance green" or Cg component of YCoCg, with 0.5f more green
13592     * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
13593     * @return a libGDX Color with the given properties
13594     */
13595    public static Color ycocg(float y, float co, float cg, float opacity) {
13596//        if (luma <= 0.0039f) {
13597//            return floatGet(0f, 0f, 0f, opacity);
13598//        } else if (luma >= 0.9961f) {
13599//            return floatGet(1f, 1f, 1f, opacity);
13600//        }
13601//        if (co >= -0.0039f && co <= 0.0039f && cg >= -0.0039f && cg <= 0.0039f) {
13602//            return floatGet(y, y, y, opacity);
13603//        }
13604        /*
13605t = Y - Cg;
13606R = t + Co;
13607G = Y + Cg;
13608B = t - Co;
13609         */
13610        final float t = y - cg;
13611        return new Color(MathUtils.clamp(t + co, 0f, 1f),
13612                MathUtils.clamp(y + cg, 0f, 1f),
13613                MathUtils.clamp(t - co, 0f, 1f),
13614                opacity);
13615    }
13616    /**
13617     * Gets a color as a packed float given floats representing luma (Y, akin to lightness), chroma warm (Cw, one of two
13618     * kinds of chroma used here), chroma mild (Cm, the other kind of chroma), and opacity. Luma should be between 0 and
13619     * 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors including but not limited to black, and 1 used for very light
13620     * colors including but not limited to white. The two chroma values range from -1.0 to 1.0, unlike YCbCr and YCoCg,
13621     * and also unlike those color spaces, there's some aesthetic value in changing just one chroma value. When warm is
13622     * high and mild is low, the color is more reddish; when both are low it is more bluish, and when mild is high and
13623     * warm is low, the color tends to be greenish, and when both are high it tends to be brown or yellow. When warm and
13624     * mild are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because chroma values are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply
13625     * them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color.
13626     * <br>
13627     * This method clamps the resulting color's RGB values, so any values can technically be given to this as luma,
13628     * warm, and mild, but they will only be reversible from the returned float color to the original Y, Cw, and Cm
13629     * values if the original values were in the range that {@link #chromaWarm(float)}, {@link #chromaMild(float)}, and
13630     * {@link #lumaYCwCm(float)} return.
13631     *
13632     * @param luma       0f to 1f, luma or Y component of YCwCm
13633     * @param warm       -1f to 1f, "chroma warm" or Cw component of YCwCm, with 1f more red or yellow
13634     * @param mild       -1f to 1f, "chroma mild" or Cm component of YCwCm, with 1f more green or yellow
13635     * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
13636     * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
13637     */
13638    public static float floatGetYCwCm(float luma, float warm, float mild, float opacity) {
13639        // the color solid should be:
13640
13641        //                   > warm >
13642        // blue    violet     red
13643        // cyan     gray      orange
13644        // green    neon      yellow
13645        //  \/ mild \/
13646
13647        // so, warm is effectively defined as the presence of red.
13648        // and mild is, effectively, presence of green.
13649        // negative warm or negative mild will each contribute to blue.
13650        // luma is defined as (r * 3 + g * 4 + b) / 8
13651        // or r * 0.375f + g * 0.5f + b * 0.125f
13652        // warm is the warm-cool axis, with positive warm between red and yellow and negative warm between blue and green
13653        // warm is defined as (r - b), with range from -1 to 1
13654        // mild is the green-purple axis, with positive mild between green and yellow, negative mild between blue and red
13655        // mild is defined as (g - b), with range from -1 to 1
13656
13657        //r = (warm * 5 - mild * 4 + luma * 8) / 8; r5 - b5 - g4 + b4 + r3 + g4 + b1
13658        //g = (mild * 4 - warm * 3 + luma * 8) / 8; g4 - b4 - r3 + b3 + r3 + g4 + b1
13659        //b = (luma * 8 - warm * 3 - mild * 4) / 8; r3 + g4 + b1 - r3 + b3 - g4 + b4
13660        return floatGet(MathUtils.clamp(luma + warm * 0.625f - mild * 0.5f, 0f, 1f),
13661                MathUtils.clamp(luma + mild * 0.5f - warm * 0.375f, 0f, 1f),
13662                MathUtils.clamp(luma - warm * 0.375f - mild * 0.5f, 0f, 1f), opacity);
13663
13664    }
13665    /**
13666     * Gets a color as a packed float given floats representing luma (Y, akin to lightness), chroma warm (Cw, one of two
13667     * kinds of chroma used here), chroma mild (Cm, the other kind of chroma), and opacity. Luma should be between 0 and
13668     * 1, inclusive, with 0 used for very dark colors including but not limited to black, and 1 used for very light
13669     * colors including but not limited to white. The two chroma values range from -1.0 to 1.0, unlike YCbCr and YCoCg,
13670     * and also unlike those color spaces, there's some aesthetic value in changing just one chroma value. When warm is
13671     * high and mild is low, the color is more reddish; when both are low it is more bluish, and when mild is high and
13672     * warm is low, the color tends to be greenish, and when both are high it tends to be brown or yellow. When warm and
13673     * mild are both near 0.0f, the color is closer to gray. Because chroma values are centered on 0.0f, you can multiply
13674     * them by a value like 0.5f to halve the colorfulness of the color.
13675     * <br>
13676     * This method clamps the resulting color's RGB values, so any values can technically be given to this as luma,
13677     * warm, and mild, but they will only be reversible from the returned float color to the original Y, Cw, and Cm
13678     * values if the original values were in the range that {@link #chromaWarm(float)}, {@link #chromaMild(float)}, and
13679     * {@link #lumaYCwCm(float)} return.
13680     *
13681     * @param luma       0f to 1f, luma or Y component of YCwCm
13682     * @param warm       -1f to 1f, "chroma warm" or Cw component of YCwCm, with 1f more red or yellow
13683     * @param mild       -1f to 1f, "chroma mild" or Cm component of YCwCm, with 1f more green or yellow
13684     * @param opacity    0f to 1f, 0f is fully transparent and 1f is opaque
13685     * @return a libGDX Color with the given properties
13686     */
13687    public static Color ycwcm(float luma, float warm, float mild, float opacity) {
13688        return new Color(MathUtils.clamp(luma + warm * 0.625f - mild * 0.5f, 0f, 1f),
13689                MathUtils.clamp(luma + mild * 0.5f - warm * 0.375f, 0f, 1f),
13690                MathUtils.clamp(luma - warm * 0.375f - mild * 0.5f, 0f, 1f), opacity);
13691    }

13767            0xEA/255f, 0xEA/255f, 0xEA/255f, 0xEA/255f, 0xFF/255f, 0xFF/255f, 0xFF/255f, 0xFF/255f,
13768    };
13769    /**
13770     * The 6 possible values that can be used in the blue channel with {@link #blueLUT}.
13771     */
13772    public static final byte[] bluePossibleLUT = {0x00, 0x38, 0x76, (byte)0xAC, (byte)0xEA, (byte)0xFF};
13773
13774    /**
13775     * Reduces the color depth of the given r, g, and b color channels to fit in 252 colors plus fully transparent (an
13776     * all-0 value is used when alpha is less than 0.5f). Uses a lookup table per channel that is not perfectly accurate
13777     * to the original color's brightness, and when this quantize technique is applied to an image of a painting, it
13778     * tends to make it more bold and highly-contrasted. Returns a packed float.
13779     * @param r red channel, from 0f to 1f inclusive
13780     * @param g green channel, from 0f to 1f inclusive
13781     * @param b blue channel, from 0f to 1f inclusive
13782     * @param a alpha channel, from 0f to 1f inclusive; will only change the result if less than 0.5f
13783     * @return one of 253 possible float values with the reduced color depth, as a packed float
13784     */
13785    public static float quantize253F(float r, float g, float b, float a)
13786    {
13787        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((redLUT[(int)(r*31.999f)] | greenLUT[(int)(g*31.999f)] | blueLUT[(int)(b*31.999f)]) & -(int)(a + 0.5f));
13788    }
13789
13790    /**
13791     * Reduces the color depth of the given packed float color to fit in 252 colors plus fully transparent (an all-0
13792     * value is used when alpha is less than 0.5f). Uses a lookup table per channel that is not perfectly accurate to
13793     * the original color's brightness, and when this quantize technique is applied to an image of a painting, it tends
13794     * to make it more bold and highly-contrasted. Returns a packed float.
13795     * @param packed a packed float color, as returned by {@link #toFloatBits()}
13796     * @return a possibly-different packed float color that has been reduced in color depth
13797     */
13798    public static float quantize253F(float packed)
13799    {
13800        final int unpacked = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(packed);
13801        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((redLUT[unpacked >>> 3 & 31] | greenLUT[unpacked >>> 11 & 31] | blueLUT[unpacked >>> 19 & 31]) & unpacked >> 31);
13802    }
13803
13804    /**
13805     * Reduces the color depth of the given packed float color to fit in 252 colors plus fully transparent (an all-0
13806     * value is used when alpha is less than 0.5f) and returns the color as an RGBA8888 int. Uses a lookup table per
13807     * channel that is not perfectly accurate to the original color's brightness, and when this quantize technique is
13808     * applied to an image of a painting, it tends to make it more bold and highly-contrasted. Returns an int.
13809     * @param packed a packed float color, as returned by {@link #toFloatBits()}
13810     * @return an int representing an RGBA8888 color
13811     */
13812    public static int quantize253I(float packed)
13813    {
13814        final int unpacked = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(packed);
13815        return Integer.reverseBytes((redLUT[unpacked >>> 3 & 31] | greenLUT[unpacked >>> 11 & 31] | blueLUT[unpacked >>> 19 & 31]) & unpacked >> 31);
13816    }
13817    /**
13818     * Reduces the color depth of the given Color to fit in 252 colors plus fully transparent (an all-0 value is used
13819     * when alpha is less than 0.5f) and returns the color as an RGBA8888 int. Uses a lookup table per channel that is
13820     * not perfectly accurate to the original color's brightness, and when this quantize technique is applied to an
13821     * image of a painting, it tends to make it more bold and highly-contrasted. Returns an int.
13822     * @param color a libGDX Color, will not be modified
13823     * @return an int representing an RGBA8888 color
13824     */
13825    public static int quantize253I(Color color)
13826    {
13827        return Integer.reverseBytes((redLUT[(int)(color.r*31.999f)] | greenLUT[(int)(color.g*31.999f)] | blueLUT[(int)(color.b*31.999f)]) & -(int)(color.a + 0.5));
13828    }
13829
13830    /**
13831     * Reduces the color depth of the given Color and returns a new Color that fits in 252 colors plus fully transparent
13832     * (an all-0 value is used when alpha is less than 0.5f). Uses a lookup table per channel that is not perfectly
13833     * accurate to the original color's brightness, and when this quantize technique is applied to an image of a
13834     * painting, it tends to make it more bold and highly-contrasted. Returns a new Color and does not change this
13835     * SColor object.
13836     * @return a new Color that must be one of 253 possible quantized colors
13837     */
13838    public Color quantize253()
13839    {
13840        if(a >= 0.5f) 
13841            return new Color(redLUTf[(int)(r*31.999f)], greenLUTf[(int)(g*31.999f)], blueLUTf[(int)(b*31.999f)], 1f);
13842        else
13843            return new Color(0f, 0f, 0f, 0f);
13844    }

13846    /**
13847     * Converts a packed float color in the format produced by {@link #toFloatBits()} to an RGBA8888 int. This format of
13848     * int can be used with Pixmap and in some other places in libGDX.
13849     * @param packed a packed float color, as produced by {@link #toFloatBits()}
13850     * @return an RGBA8888 int color
13851     */
13852    public static int floatToInt(final float packed)
13853    {
13854        return NumberTools.floatToReversedIntBits(packed);
13855    }

13857    /**
13858     * Gets a variation on this SColor as a packed float that can have its hue, saturation, and value changed to
13859     * specified degrees using a random number generator. Takes an IRNG object (if the colors don't have a specific need
13860     * to be exactly the same each run, consider using {@link DefaultResources#getGuiRandom()} for an IRNG), as well as
13861     * floats representing the amounts of change that can be applied to hue, saturation, and value. Returns a float that
13862     * can be used as a packed or encoded color with methods like
13863     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}, or in various SquidLib classes like SparseLayers or
13864     * SquidLayers. The float is likely to be different than the result of {@link #toFloatBits()} unless hue,
13865     * saturation, and value are all 0. This won't modify the current SColor, nor will it allocate any objects.
13866     * <br>
13867     * The parameters this takes (other than random) all specify spans that the value can change by, spread halfway
13868     * toward higher values and halfway towards lower values. This is truncated if it would make a value lower than 0 or
13869     * higher than 1, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around somewhat if lower or higher hues would be used.
13870     * As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the possible
13871     * saturations that could be used would have the specified 0.4f range centered on 0.7f, or 0.5f to 0.9f. If you gave
13872     * this 1f for saturation and the current color still has saturation 0.7f, then the range would be truncated at the
13873     * upper end, for a possible range of 0.2f to 1.0f. If truncation of the range occurs, then values are more likely
13874     * to be at the truncated max or min amount.
13875     *
13876     * @param random     an IRNG to get random amounts, such as {@link DefaultResources#getGuiRandom()}
13877     * @param hue        0f to 1f, the span of hue change that can be applied to the new float color
13878     * @param saturation 0f to 1f, the span of saturation change that can be applied to the new float color
13879     * @param value      0f to 1f, the span of value/brightness change that can be applied to the new float color
13880     * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
13881     */
13882    public float toRandomizedFloat(IRNG random, float hue, float saturation, float value) {
13883        return toRandomizedFloat(this, random, hue, saturation, value, 0f);
13884    }

13895     * saturation, and value are all 0. This won't modify the current SColor, nor will it allocate any objects.

13923     * SquidLayers. The float is likely to be different than the result of {@link #toFloatBits()} unless hue,
13924     * saturation, value, and opacity are all 0. This won't modify the current SColor, nor will it allocate any objects.
13925     * <br>
13926     * The parameters this takes (other than random) all specify spans that the value can change by, spread halfway
13927     * toward higher values and halfway towards lower values. This is truncated if it would make a value lower than 0 or
13928     * higher than 1, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around somewhat if lower or higher hues would be used.
13929     * As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the possible
13930     * saturations that could be used would have the specified 0.4f range centered on 0.7f, or 0.5f to 0.9f. If you gave
13931     * this 1f for saturation and the current color still has saturation 0.7f, then the range would be truncated at the

13942    public float toRandomizedFloat(IRNG random, float hue, float saturation, float value, float opacity) {

13945    /**
13946     * Gets a variation on the Color basis as a packed float that can have its hue, saturation, value, and opacity
13947     * changed to specified degrees using a random number generator. Takes an IRNG object (if the colors don't have a
13948     * specific need to be exactly the same each run, consider using {@link DefaultResources#getGuiRandom()} for an
13949     * IRNG), as well as floats representing the amounts of change that can be applied to hue, saturation, value, and
13950     * opacity. Returns a float that can be used as a packed or encoded color with methods like
13951     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}, or in various SquidLib classes like SparseLayers or
13952     * SquidLayers. The float is likely to be different than the result of {@link #toFloatBits()} unless hue,
13953     * saturation, value, and opacity are all 0. This won't modify the current SColor, nor will it allocate any objects.
13954     * <br>
13955     * The parameters this takes (other than random) all specify spans that the value can change by, spread halfway
13956     * toward higher values and halfway towards lower values. This is truncated if it would make a value lower than 0 or
13957     * higher than 1, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around somewhat if lower or higher hues would be used.
13958     * As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the possible
13959     * saturations that could be used would have the specified 0.4f range centered on 0.7f, or 0.5f to 0.9f. If you gave
13960     * this 1f for saturation and the current color still has saturation 0.7f, then the range would be truncated at the
13961     * upper end, for a possible range of 0.2f to 1.0f. If truncation of the range occurs, then values are more likely
13962     * to be at the truncated max or min amount.
13963     *
13964     * @param basis      a Color or SColor to use as the starting point; will not be modified itself
13965     * @param random     an IRNG to get random amounts, such as {@link DefaultResources#getGuiRandom()}
13966     * @param hue        0f to 2f, the span of hue change that can be applied to the new float color
13967     * @param saturation 0f to 2f, the span of saturation change that can be applied to the new float color
13968     * @param value      0f to 2f, the span of value/brightness change that can be applied to the new float color
13969     * @param opacity    0f to 2f, the span of opacity/alpha change that can be applied to the new float color
13970     * @return a float encoding a variation of this SColor with changes up to the given properties
13971     */
13972    public static float toRandomizedFloat(Color basis, IRNG random, float hue, float saturation, float value, float opacity) {
13973        final float h, s, r = basis.r, g = basis.g, b = basis.b;
13974        final float min = Math.min(Math.min(r, g), b);   //Min. value of RGB
13975        final float max = Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b);   //Max value of RGB, equivalent to value
13976        final float delta = max - min;                   //Delta RGB value
13977        if ( delta < 0.0039f )                           //This is a gray, no chroma...
13978        {
13979            s = 0f;
13980            h = 0f;
13981            hue = 1f;
13982        }
13983        else                                             //Chromatic data...
13984        {
13985            s = delta / max;
13986            final float rDelta = (((max - r) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
13987            final float gDelta = (((max - g) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
13988            final float bDelta = (((max - b) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
13989
13990            if      (r == max) h = (bDelta - gDelta + 1f) % 1f;
13991            else if (g == max) h = ((1f / 3f) + rDelta - bDelta + 1f) % 1f;
13992            else               h = ((2f / 3f) + gDelta - rDelta + 1f) % 1f;
13993        }
13994        saturation = MathUtils.clamp(s + (random.nextFloat() - 0.5f) * saturation, 0f, 1f);
13995        value = MathUtils.clamp(max + (random.nextFloat() - 0.5f) * value, 0f, 1f);
13996        opacity = MathUtils.clamp(basis.a + (random.nextFloat() - 0.5f) * opacity, 0f, 1f);
13997
13998        if (saturation <= 0.0039f) {
13999            return floatGet(value, value, value, opacity);
14000        } else if (value <= 0.0039f) {
14001            return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((int) (opacity * 254f) << 24 & 0xFE000000);
14002        } else {
14003            final float hu = ((h + (random.nextFloat() - 0.5f) * hue + 6f) % 1f) * 6f;
14004            final int i = (int) hu;
14005            final float x = value * (1 - saturation);
14006            final float y = value * (1 - saturation * (hu - i));
14007            final float z = value * (1 - saturation * (1 - (hu - i)));
14008
14009            switch (i) {
14010                case 0:
14011                    return floatGet(value, z, x, opacity);
14012                case 1:
14013                    return floatGet(y, value, x, opacity);
14014                case 2:
14015                    return floatGet(x, value, z, opacity);
14016                case 3:
14017                    return floatGet(x, y, value, opacity);
14018                case 4:
14019                    return floatGet(z, x, value, opacity);
14020                default:
14021                    return floatGet(value, x, y, opacity);
14022            }
14023        }
14024    }

14026     * Gets a variation on this SColor as a packed float that has its hue, saturation, and value adjusted by the
14027     * specified amounts. Takes floats representing the amounts of change to apply to hue, saturation, and value; these
14028     * can be between -1f and 1f. Returns a float that can be used as a packed or encoded color with methods like
14029     * {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}, or in various SquidLib classes like SparseLayers or
14030     * SquidLayers. The float is likely to be different than the result of {@link #toFloatBits()} unless hue,
14031     * saturation, and value are all 0. This won't modify the current SColor, nor will it allocate any objects.
14032     * <br>
14033     * The parameters this takes all specify additive changes for a color component, clamping the final values so they
14034     * can't go above 1 or below 0, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around if lower or higher hues would be
14035     * used. As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the
14036     * resulting color will have 1f for saturation. If you gave this -0.1f for saturation and the current color still
14037     * has saturation 0.7f, then resulting color will have 0.6f for saturation.
14038     *
14039     * @param hue        -1f to 1f, the hue change that can be applied to the new float color
14040     * @param saturation -1f to 1f, the saturation change that can be applied to the new float color
14041     * @param value      -1f to 1f, the value/brightness change that can be applied to the new float color
14042     * @return a float encoding a color with the given properties
14043     */
14044    public float toEditedFloat(float hue, float saturation, float value) {
14045        return toEditedFloat(this, hue, saturation, value, 0f);
14046    }

14095    /**
14096     * Gets a variation on the Color basis as a packed float that has its hue, saturation, value, and opacity adjusted
14097     * by the specified amounts. Takes floats representing the amounts of change to apply to hue, saturation, value, and
14098     * opacity; these can be between -1f and 1f. Returns a float that can be used as a packed or encoded color with
14099     * methods like {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}, or in various SquidLib classes like
14100     * SparseLayers or SquidLayers. The float is likely to be different than the result of {@link #toFloatBits()} unless
14101     * hue saturation, value, and opacity are all 0. This won't modify the given SColor, nor will it allocate any
14102     * objects.
14103     * <br>
14104     * The parameters this takes all specify additive changes for a color component, clamping the final values so they
14105     * can't go above 1 or below 0, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around if lower or higher hues would be
14106     * used. As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the
14107     * resulting color will have 1f for saturation. If you gave this -0.1f for saturation and the current color still
14108     * has saturation 0.7f, then resulting color will have 0.6f for saturation.
14109     *
14110     * @param hue        -1f to 1f, the hue change that can be applied to the new float color
14111     * @param saturation -1f to 1f, the saturation change that can be applied to the new float color
14112     * @param value      -1f to 1f, the value/brightness change that can be applied to the new float color
14113     * @param opacity    -1f to 1f, the opacity/alpha change that can be applied to the new float color
14114     * @return a float encoding a variation of basis with the given changes
14115     */
14116    public static float toEditedFloat(Color basis, float hue, float saturation, float value, float opacity) {
14117        final float h, s, r = basis.r, g = basis.g, b = basis.b;
14118        final float min = Math.min(Math.min(r, g), b);   //Min. value of RGB
14119        final float max = Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b);   //Max value of RGB, equivalent to value
14120        final float delta = max - min;                   //Delta RGB value
14121        if ( delta < 0.0039f )                           //This is a gray, no chroma...
14122        {
14123            s = 0f;
14124            h = 0f;
14125            hue = 1f;
14126        }
14127        else                                             //Chromatic data...
14128        {
14129            s = delta / max;
14130            final float rDelta = (((max - r) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
14131            final float gDelta = (((max - g) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
14132            final float bDelta = (((max - b) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
14133
14134            if      (r == max) h = (bDelta - gDelta + 1f) % 1f;
14135            else if (g == max) h = ((1f / 3f) + rDelta - bDelta + 1f) % 1f;
14136            else               h = ((2f / 3f) + gDelta - rDelta + 1f) % 1f;
14137        }
14138        saturation = MathUtils.clamp(s + saturation, 0f, 1f);
14139        value = MathUtils.clamp(max + value, 0f, 1f);
14140        opacity = MathUtils.clamp(basis.a + opacity, 0f, 1f);
14141
14142        if (saturation <= 0.0039f) {
14143            return floatGet(value, value, value, opacity);
14144        } else if (value <= 0.0039f) {
14145            return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((int) (opacity * 254f) << 24 & 0xFE000000);
14146        } else {
14147            final float hu = ((h + hue + 6f) % 1f) * 6f;
14148            final int i = (int) hu;
14149            final float x = value * (1 - saturation);
14150            final float y = value * (1 - saturation * (hu - i));
14151            final float z = value * (1 - saturation * (1 - (hu - i)));
14152
14153            switch (i) {
14154                case 0:
14155                    return floatGet(value, z, x, opacity);
14156                case 1:
14157                    return floatGet(y, value, x, opacity);
14158                case 2:
14159                    return floatGet(x, value, z, opacity);
14160                case 3:
14161                    return floatGet(x, y, value, opacity);
14162                case 4:
14163                    return floatGet(z, x, value, opacity);
14164                default:
14165                    return floatGet(value, x, y, opacity);
14166            }
14167        }
14168    }
14169    /**
14170     * Gets a variation on the packed float color basis as another packed float that has its hue, saturation, value, and
14171     * opacity adjusted by the specified amounts. Takes floats representing the amounts of change to apply to hue,
14172     * saturation, value, and opacity; these can be between -1f and 1f. Returns a float that can be used as a packed or
14173     * encoded color with methods like {@link com.badlogic.gdx.graphics.g2d.Batch#setPackedColor(float)}, or in various
14174     * SquidLib classes like SparseLayers or SquidLayers. The float is likely to be different than the result of
14175     * {@link #toFloatBits()} unless hue saturation, value, and opacity are all 0. This won't allocate any objects.
14176     * <br>
14177     * The parameters this takes all specify additive changes for a color component, clamping the final values so they
14178     * can't go above 1 or below 0, with an exception for hue, which can rotate around if lower or higher hues would be
14179     * used. As an example, if you give this 0.4f for saturation, and the current color has saturation 0.7f, then the
14180     * resulting color will have 1f for saturation. If you gave this -0.1f for saturation and the current color again
14181     * has saturation 0.7f, then resulting color will have 0.6f for saturation.
14182     *
14183     * @param basis      a packed float color that will be used as the starting point to make the next color
14184     * @param hue        -1f to 1f, the hue change that can be applied to the new float color (not clamped, wraps)
14185     * @param saturation -1f to 1f, the saturation change that can be applied to the new float color
14186     * @param value      -1f to 1f, the value/brightness change that can be applied to the new float color
14187     * @param opacity    -1f to 1f, the opacity/alpha change that can be applied to the new float color
14188     * @return a float encoding a variation of basis with the given changes
14189     */
14190    public static float toEditedFloat(float basis, float hue, float saturation, float value, float opacity) {
14191        final int bits = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(basis);
14192        final float h, s,
14193                r = (bits & 0x000000ff) * 0x1.010102p-8f,
14194                g = (bits & 0x0000ff00) * 0x1.010102p-16f,
14195                b = (bits & 0x00ff0000) * 0x1.010102p-24f;
14196        final float min = Math.min(Math.min(r, g), b);   //Min. value of RGB
14197        final float max = Math.max(Math.max(r, g), b);   //Max value of RGB, equivalent to value
14198        final float delta = max - min;                   //Delta RGB value
14199        if ( delta < 0.0039f )                           //This is a gray, no chroma...
14200        {
14201            s = 0f;
14202            h = 0f;
14203            hue = 1f;
14204        }
14205        else                                             //Chromatic data...
14206        {
14207            s = delta / max;
14208            final float rDelta = (((max - r) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
14209            final float gDelta = (((max - g) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
14210            final float bDelta = (((max - b) / 6f) + (delta / 2f)) / delta;
14211
14212            if      (r == max) h = (bDelta - gDelta + 1f) % 1f;
14213            else if (g == max) h = ((1f / 3f) + rDelta - bDelta + 1f) % 1f;
14214            else               h = ((2f / 3f) + gDelta - rDelta + 1f) % 1f;
14215        }
14216        saturation = MathUtils.clamp(s + saturation, 0f, 1f);
14217        value = MathUtils.clamp(max + value, 0f, 1f);
14218        opacity = MathUtils.clamp(((bits & 0xfe000000) >>> 24) * 0x1.020408p-8f + opacity, 0f, 1f);
14219
14220        if (saturation <= 0.0039f) {
14221            return floatGet(value, value, value, opacity);
14222        } else if (value <= 0.0039f) {
14223            return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat((int) (opacity * 254f) << 24 & 0xFE000000);
14224        } else {
14225            final float hu = ((h + hue + 6f) % 1f) * 6f;
14226            final int i = (int) hu;
14227            final float x = value * (1 - saturation);
14228            final float y = value * (1 - saturation * (hu - i));
14229            final float z = value * (1 - saturation * (1 - (hu - i)));
14230
14231            switch (i) {
14232                case 0:
14233                    return floatGet(value, z, x, opacity);
14234                case 1:
14235                    return floatGet(y, value, x, opacity);
14236                case 2:
14237                    return floatGet(x, value, z, opacity);
14238                case 3:
14239                    return floatGet(x, y, value, opacity);
14240                case 4:
14241                    return floatGet(z, x, value, opacity);
14242                default:
14243                    return floatGet(value, x, y, opacity);
14244            }
14245        }
14246    }
14247
14248    /**
14249     * Interpolates from the packed float color start towards end by change. Both start and end should be packed colors,
14250     * as from {@link #toFloatBits()} or {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}, and change can be between 0f
14251     * (keep start) and 1f (only use end). This is a good way to reduce allocations of temporary Colors.
14252     * @param start the starting color as a packed float
14253     * @param end the target color as a packed float
14254     * @param change how much to go from start toward end, as a float between 0 and 1; higher means closer to end
14255     * @return a packed float that represents a color between start and end
14256     */
14257    public static float lerpFloatColors(final float start, final float end, final float change) {
14258        final int s = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(start), e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(end),
14259                rs = (s & 0xFF), gs = (s >>> 8) & 0xFF, bs = (s >>> 16) & 0xFF, as = (s >>> 24) & 254,
14260                re = (e & 0xFF), ge = (e >>> 8) & 0xFF, be = (e >>> 16) & 0xFF, ae = (e >>> 24) & 254;
14261        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(((int) (rs + change * (re - rs)) & 0xFF)
14262                | (((int) (gs + change * (ge - gs)) & 0xFF) << 8)
14263                | (((int) (bs + change * (be - bs)) & 0xFF) << 16)
14264                | (((int) (as + change * (ae - as)) & 0xFE) << 24));
14265    }
14266
14267    /**
14268     * Interpolates from the packed float color start towards end by change, but keeps the alpha of start and uses the
14269     * alpha of end as an extra factor that can affect how much to change. Both start and end should be packed colors,
14270     * as from {@link #toFloatBits()} or {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}, and change can be between 0f
14271     * (keep start) and 1f (only use end). This is a good way to reduce allocations of temporary Colors.
14272     * @param start the starting color as a packed float; alpha will be preserved
14273     * @param end the target color as a packed float; alpha will not be used directly, and will instead be multiplied with change
14274     * @param change how much to go from start toward end, as a float between 0 and 1; higher means closer to end
14275     * @return a packed float that represents a color between start and end
14276     */
14277    public static float lerpFloatColorsBlended(final float start, final float end, float change) {
14278        final int s = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(start), e = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(end),
14279                rs = (s & 0xFF), gs = (s >>> 8) & 0xFF, bs = (s >>> 16) & 0xFF, as = s & 0xFE000000,
14280                re = (e & 0xFF), ge = (e >>> 8) & 0xFF, be = (e >>> 16) & 0xFF, ae = (e >>> 25);
14281        change *= ae * 0.007874016f;
14282        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(((int) (rs + change * (re - rs)) & 0xFF)
14283                | (((int) (gs + change * (ge - gs)) & 0xFF) << 8)
14284                | (((int) (bs + change * (be - bs)) & 0xFF) << 16)
14285                | as);
14286    }
14287
14288    /**
14289     * Interpolates from the packed float color start towards white by change. While change should be between 0f (return
14290     * start as-is) and 1f (return white), start should be a packed color, as from {@link #toFloatBits()} or
14291     * {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}. This is a good way to reduce allocations of temporary Colors, and
14292     * is a little more efficient and clear than using {@link #lerpFloatColors(float, float, float)} to lerp towards
14293     * white. Unlike {@link #lerpFloatColors(float, float, float)}, this keeps the alpha of start as-is.
14294     * @param start the starting color as a packed float
14295     * @param change how much to go from start toward white, as a float between 0 and 1; higher means closer to end
14296     * @return a packed float that represents a color between start and white
14297     */
14298    public static float lightenFloat(final float start, final float change) {
14299        final int s = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(start),
14300                rs = (s & 0xFF), gs = (s >>> 8) & 0xFF, bs = (s >>> 16) & 0xFF, as = s & 0xFE000000;
14301        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(((int) (rs + change * (0xFF - rs)) & 0xFF)
14302                | (((int) (gs + change * (0xFF - gs)) & 0xFF) << 8)
14303                | (((int) (bs + change * (0xFF - bs)) & 0xFF) << 16)
14304                | as);
14305    }
14306
14307    /**
14308     * Interpolates from the packed float color start towards black by change. While change should be between 0f (return
14309     * start as-is) and 1f (return black), start should be a packed color, as from {@link #toFloatBits()} or
14310     * {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}. This is a good way to reduce allocations of temporary Colors, and
14311     * is a little more efficient and clear than using {@link #lerpFloatColors(float, float, float)} to lerp towards
14312     * black. Unlike {@link #lerpFloatColors(float, float, float)}, this keeps the alpha of start as-is.
14313     * @param start the starting color as a packed float
14314     * @param change how much to go from start toward black, as a float between 0 and 1; higher means closer to end
14315     * @return a packed float that represents a color between start and black
14316     */
14317    public static float darkenFloat(final float start, float change) {
14318        final int s = NumberTools.floatToIntBits(start),
14319                rs = (s & 0xFF), gs = (s >>> 8) & 0xFF, bs = (s >>> 16) & 0xFF, as = s & 0xFE000000;
14320        change = 1f - change;
14321        return NumberTools.intBitsToFloat(((int) (rs * change) & 0xFF)
14322                | (((int) (gs * change) & 0xFF) << 8)
14323                | (((int) (bs * change) & 0xFF) << 16)
14324                | as);
14325    }
14326
14327
14328    /**
14329     * Similar to {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)}, but meant for an initial state before you have FOV or color
14330     * data to fill the lighting with, and you just need a map of a specific size that starts with no lighting. This
14331     * will produce a map that has white as the lighting color for all cells, but no cells will be lit. It is likely you
14332     * will want to pass this as basis to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])}.
14333     *
14334     * @param width  the width of the colored lighting area to generate
14335     * @param height the height of the colored lighting area to generate
14336     * @return the colored lighting 3D float array, with no cells lit and all colors set to white
14337     */
14338    public static float[][][] blankColoredLighting(int width, int height) {
14339        return new float[][][]
14340                {
14341                        new float[width][height],
14342                        ArrayTools.fill(FLOAT_WHITE, width, height)
14343                };
14344    }
14345
14346    /**
14347     * Removes any information from the given 3D float array for colored lighting, making it as if it had just been
14348     * built by {@link #blankColoredLighting(int, int)}, but without any allocations. This blank state is different from
14349     * being simply filled with all 0 or all default values; the two sub-arrays receive different contents (the one that
14350     * stores brightness is all 0, the one that stores colors will be filled with the float that encodes white).
14351     *
14352     * @param original a 3d float array used for colored lighting; will be modified to be completely blank
14353     * @return original, after modification
14354     */
14355    public static float[][][] eraseColoredLighting(float[][][] original) {
14356        ArrayTools.fill(original[0], 0f);
14357        ArrayTools.fill(original[1], FLOAT_WHITE);
14358        return original;
14359    }
14360
14361    /**
14362     * Given a 2D double array that was probably produced by FOV and a packed color as a float, this gets a 3D float
14363     * array (really just two same-size 2D float arrays in one parent array) that stores the brightnesses in the first
14364     * 2D array element and the colors in the second 2D array element (using the given color if a cell has a value in
14365     * lights that is greater than 0, or defaulting to white if the cell is unlit). This has little use on its own, and
14366     * is meant to be given to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])} so that multiple colors of lights
14367     * can be mixed.
14368     *
14369     * @param lights a 2D double array that should probably come from FOV
14370     * @param color  a packed float as produced by {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}
14371     * @return a 3D float array containing two 2D sub-arrays, the first holding brightness and the second holding color
14372     */
14373    public static float[][][] colorLighting(double[][] lights, float color) {
14374        return colorLightingInto(new float[2][lights.length][lights[0].length], lights, color);
14375    }
14376
14377    /**
14378     * Given a 2D double array that was probably produced by FOV and a packed color as a float, this assigns into reuse
14379     * a 3D float array (really just two same-size 2D float arrays in one parent array) that stores the brightnesses in
14380     * the first 2D array element and the colors in the second 2D array element (using the given color if a cell has a
14381     * value in lights that is greater than 0, or defaulting to white if the cell is unlit). This method requires that
14382     * reuse has length of at least 2, where elements 0 and 1 must be 2D arrays of identical dimensions; this is the
14383     * format that {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} produces. This has little use on its own, and  is meant to
14384     * be given to {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])} so that multiple colors of lights can be mixed.
14385     *
14386     * @param reuse  a 3D float array of the exact format produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} or
14387     *               {@link #mixColoredLighting(float[][][], float[][][])}, and must have length 2; will be modified!
14388     * @param lights a 2D double array that should probably come from FOV
14389     * @param color  a packed float as produced by {@link #floatGet(float, float, float, float)}
14390     * @return reuse after modification
14391     */
14392    public static float[][][] colorLightingInto(float[][][] reuse, double[][] lights, float color) {
14393        for (int x = 0; x < lights.length; x++) {
14394            for (int y = 0; y < lights[0].length; y++) {
14395                reuse[1][x][y] = ((reuse[0][x][y] = (float) lights[x][y]) > 0f)
14396                        ? color
14397                        : FLOAT_WHITE;
14398            }
14399        }
14400        return reuse;
14401    }
14402
14403    /**
14404     * Adds two 3D arrays produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)} or this method and modifies the basis
14405     * parameter so it contains the combined brightnesses and colors of basis and other, in a pair of 2D arrays.
14406     *
14407     * @param basis a 3D float array holding two 2D sub-arrays, as produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)};
14408     *              will be modified to contain its existing contents mixed with other's contents 
14409     * @param other a 3D float array holding two 2D sub-arrays, as produced by {@link #colorLighting(double[][], float)};
14410     *              will not be modified
14411     * @return basis, after modification; it can be passed to this method as basis again
14412     */
14413    public static float[][][] mixColoredLighting(float[][][] basis, float[][][] other) {
14414        int w = basis[0].length, h = basis[0][0].length, w2 = other[0].length, h2 = other[0][0].length;
14415        for (int x = 0; x < w && x < w2; x++) {
14416            for (int y = 0; y < h && y < h2; y++) {
14417                basis[1][x][y] = (basis[1][x][y] == FLOAT_WHITE)
14418                        ? other[1][x][y]
14419                        : (other[1][x][y] == FLOAT_WHITE)
14420                        ? basis[1][x][y]
14421                        : lerpFloatColors(basis[1][x][y], other[1][x][y], (other[0][x][y] - basis[0][x][y]) * 0.5f + 0.5f);
14422                basis[0][x][y] = Math.min(1.0f, basis[0][x][y] + other[0][x][y]);
14423            }
14424        }
14425        return basis;
14426    }

14429    @Override
14430    public String toString() {
14431        return name + " " + super.toString();
14432    }
14433
14434    public String getName() {
14435        return name;
14436    }
14437
14438    @Override
14439    public boolean equals(Object other) {
14440        return (other instanceof Color) && toIntBits() == ((Color) other).toIntBits();
14441    }
14442
14443    @Override
14444    public int hashCode() {
14445        return (155 + CrossHash.hash(name)) * 31 ^ toIntBits();
14446    }
